1
00:00:23,125 --> 00:00:24,990
[WIND HOWLING]

2
00:00:57,625 --> 00:00:59,707
[WIND STOPS]

3
00:01:31,833 --> 00:01:33,915
[TRAIN ENGINE CHUGGING]

4
00:01:57,583 --> 00:01:59,164
[CLANG]

5
00:02:00,583 --> 00:02:02,039
[RUMBLING]

6
00:02:02,125 --> 00:02:04,116
[BRAKES SCREECHING]

7
00:02:23,542 --> 00:02:25,624
[PEOPLE MURMURING]

8
00:02:49,917 --> 00:02:51,282
[MAN] Boys!

9
00:03:02,792 --> 00:03:04,874
I hope you brought your Checkbooks.

10
00:03:06,708 --> 00:03:08,664
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

11
00:03:27,333 --> 00:03:29,995
[WOMAN] The air brakes pay
for George's latest obsession.

12
00:03:30,083 --> 00:03:32,540
By changing the dimensions of his pipes,

13
00:03:32,625 --> 00:03:36,197
George can move natural gas
over 20 miles from the well.

14
00:03:36,292 --> 00:03:38,032
Shooting, like a gun.

15
00:03:38,125 --> 00:03:40,832
Is that good or bad, Mrs. Westinghouse?

16
00:03:42,292 --> 00:03:44,954
- How is your daughter, Gladys?
- Oh, quite well, thank you.

17
00:03:45,042 --> 00:03:46,907
She's met a financier.

18
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:49,286
The beading on your dress is exquisite.

19
00:03:50,375 --> 00:03:54,698
Mr. Westinghouse, I saw in The World
Mr. Edison's new electric system

20
00:03:54,792 --> 00:03:57,408
is significantly cheaper than gas.

21
00:03:57,500 --> 00:03:59,741
Does that keep you up at night?

22
00:03:59,833 --> 00:04:01,824
There's always more to see.

23
00:04:02,792 --> 00:04:05,499
Mr. and Mrs. Worthington, Mr. Manesberg,

24
00:04:05,583 --> 00:04:08,871
Dr. and Mrs. Burton,
Reverend Vincent, Mr. McCoy,

25
00:04:08,958 --> 00:04:11,244
Mr. Faulk, Miss Faulk, enjoy your evening.

26
00:04:24,208 --> 00:04:27,905
Edison says he's months away
from lighting up the world.

27
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:31,913
It's impressive, but trust me,
it's ten years away from being practical.

28
00:04:33,000 --> 00:04:35,958
The papers make it sound
as though this is something different.

29
00:04:37,292 --> 00:04:38,657
A miracle.

30
00:04:39,583 --> 00:04:42,199
As if you started to levitate
off the carpet.

31
00:04:43,792 --> 00:04:46,033
I'd love to meet him.
Could you arrange it?

32
00:04:46,125 --> 00:04:47,365
It's been several years...

33
00:04:47,458 --> 00:04:49,699
A dinner.
Comfortable. Elegant. Substantive.

34
00:04:49,792 --> 00:04:53,410
Edison can't be bothered to tie his shoes,
let alone attend a social event.

35
00:04:53,500 --> 00:04:56,287
[CHUCKLES] Perhaps you're right.
But try anyway.

36
00:04:59,875 --> 00:05:02,036
Anything fascinating?

37
00:05:02,125 --> 00:05:05,697
Mr. Pennoyer has found a bargain
on a Beaux Arts shack in Newport.

38
00:05:05,792 --> 00:05:08,829
Mrs. Abernathy's mother has passed,
and apparently Edison believes

39
00:05:08,917 --> 00:05:11,033
it may never be nighttime again.

40
00:05:14,125 --> 00:05:16,457
- Are you excited to meet the President?
- Yes.

41
00:05:16,542 --> 00:05:18,578
Don't say a thing
about JP. Morgan's nose.

42
00:05:18,667 --> 00:05:20,282
- What's wrong with his nose?
- Nothing.

43
00:05:20,375 --> 00:05:23,822
- What's wrong with his nose?
- It's huge. Huge!

44
00:05:23,917 --> 00:05:26,533
It's like someone took a hammer
and slammed it into his face.

45
00:05:26,625 --> 00:05:28,268
[WOMAN]
I thought you already got the money.

46
00:05:28,292 --> 00:05:29,623
[MAN] I only got half.

47
00:05:29,708 --> 00:05:31,309
[WOMAN] Does Morgan even know
that you're coming?

48
00:05:31,333 --> 00:05:33,198
He'll invest as always. I hate this.

49
00:05:33,292 --> 00:05:35,052
- Mr. Edison, you have dinner with...
- What?

50
00:05:35,125 --> 00:05:36,956
Dinner with Westinghouse. On your return.

51
00:05:37,042 --> 00:05:38,282
[GIRL] Why are barns red?

52
00:05:38,375 --> 00:05:40,059
[WOMAN] Maybe so you can
see them in the snow.

53
00:05:40,083 --> 00:05:41,893
- [MAN] It's 'cause red paint's cheapest.
- What happened to your shoes?

54
00:05:41,917 --> 00:05:44,283
Morgan will want to know
the practicality of your system.

55
00:05:44,375 --> 00:05:45,535
[GIRL] I have money.

56
00:05:45,625 --> 00:05:47,741
Enough for two small buildings
in Manhattan?

57
00:05:47,833 --> 00:05:48,868
Yes.

58
00:05:48,958 --> 00:05:49,993
Oh, good.

59
00:06:03,750 --> 00:06:05,536
This was intended to be my lunch.

60
00:06:05,625 --> 00:06:07,957
The President has asked to see
the phonograph in person.

61
00:06:08,042 --> 00:06:10,875
- I had no idea you'd be here.
- Mrs. Edison.

62
00:06:10,958 --> 00:06:12,573
Mr. Morgan. These are our children.

63
00:06:12,667 --> 00:06:15,374
Dot and Dash. Delightful.
I know what you're doing.

64
00:06:15,458 --> 00:06:18,575
How much are you short? Just how much
of my money do you want to wash away?

65
00:06:18,667 --> 00:06:21,079
Oh, as very, very much as possible.

66
00:06:21,167 --> 00:06:22,873
- Who's this?
- Samuel lnsull.

67
00:06:22,958 --> 00:06:25,620
- Mr. Edison's personal secretary.
- [DOOR OPENS]

68
00:06:25,708 --> 00:06:29,030
- Mr. Morgan, Mr. Edison.
- Which one? He's also Mr. Edison.

69
00:06:29,125 --> 00:06:30,831
The President will see you now.

70
00:06:37,250 --> 00:06:38,410
Now.

71
00:06:38,500 --> 00:06:41,742
On top of the Crumpetty Tree
the Quangle Wangle sat,

72
00:06:41,833 --> 00:06:45,496
but his face you could not see,
on account of his beaver hat.

73
00:06:46,125 --> 00:06:47,956
This is the sound of your voice.

74
00:06:50,542 --> 00:06:53,534
On top of the Crumpetty Tree
the Quangle Wangle sat,

75
00:06:53,625 --> 00:06:55,832
but his face you could not see,

76
00:06:55,917 --> 00:06:58,659
- on account of his Beaver Hat.
- Is that what I sound like?

77
00:06:58,750 --> 00:07:00,456
[GIGGLING]

78
00:07:00,542 --> 00:07:02,908
My men tell me
you're turning down $5 million.

79
00:07:03,000 --> 00:07:04,559
I'm grateful for the offer, Mr. President,

80
00:07:04,583 --> 00:07:08,121
but it's the type of science you're after
that I find objectionable.

81
00:07:08,208 --> 00:07:10,601
- There's always money in guns.
- The one device I shall never build

82
00:07:10,625 --> 00:07:12,741
is that which takes the life
of another man.

83
00:07:12,833 --> 00:07:13,948
It's barbaric.

84
00:07:15,167 --> 00:07:17,874
But... take a look at this.

85
00:07:17,958 --> 00:07:21,155
One square mile of Manhattan,
the First District.

86
00:07:21,250 --> 00:07:23,491
- And I'm gonna light it up.
- Then you have done it.

87
00:07:23,583 --> 00:07:25,949
A star in a jar. It's a warm glow.

88
00:07:26,042 --> 00:07:29,330
No smell. No poison.
Thirteen hours of light per globe.

89
00:07:29,417 --> 00:07:31,248
And it's cheaper than gas. Safer too.

90
00:07:31,333 --> 00:07:33,289
We bury the wires using my DC current,

91
00:07:33,375 --> 00:07:36,993
and those same wires
will bring you energy and heat.

92
00:07:37,875 --> 00:07:40,833
I need two buildings to house
six dynamos of my own construction.

93
00:07:40,917 --> 00:07:42,908
This won't even reach my house.

94
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:45,742
Morgan, let me make you so rich

95
00:07:45,833 --> 00:07:47,726
that you will look back
at this moment and wonder,

96
00:07:47,750 --> 00:07:49,991
"Why was I ever so disgustingly poor?"

97
00:07:50,083 --> 00:07:51,289
[MORGAN CHUCKLES]

98
00:07:52,458 --> 00:07:54,498
[EDISON] It's all right there.
Ferry to Wall Street.

99
00:07:54,583 --> 00:07:56,393
In case you missed my scribble,
that's a big old circle

100
00:07:56,417 --> 00:07:58,453
around the New York Times...
Free advertising.

101
00:07:58,542 --> 00:08:00,658
- One hundred fifty.
- Half a million.

102
00:08:00,750 --> 00:08:03,867
I'm talking about $500,000,
you buy the next century.

103
00:08:04,458 --> 00:08:05,868
Brighter, safer, yours.

104
00:08:05,958 --> 00:08:08,726
[PRESIDENT] Sounds rather grand to me,
Pierpont. If I had your fortune...

105
00:08:08,750 --> 00:08:11,082
[MORGAN]
With respect, you don't, Mr. President.

106
00:08:14,958 --> 00:08:16,914
- What is that?
- That's not very nice.

107
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:19,286
- [EDISON] Morse code.
- [DASH GIGGLES]

108
00:08:20,042 --> 00:08:21,452
[MORGAN] What did the boy say?

109
00:08:21,542 --> 00:08:22,976
- What did the boy say?
- If there's nothing else,

110
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:25,440
- it's been a pleasure, Mr. President.
- What did the boy say?

111
00:08:27,333 --> 00:08:28,994
Do you know what you've done?

112
00:08:30,083 --> 00:08:32,074
I always receive more by saying no.

113
00:08:34,125 --> 00:08:37,162
Set up the Manhattan offices
and make them look professional.

114
00:08:37,250 --> 00:08:39,332
- What does that mean?
- Oh, I don't know. Carpets.

115
00:08:40,708 --> 00:08:43,245
I don't know. Carpets. [MUMBLES]

116
00:08:43,333 --> 00:08:44,743
And the name?

117
00:08:46,500 --> 00:08:49,822
Edison Electric, of course.
Sir, why not build munitions?

118
00:08:49,917 --> 00:08:51,726
Five million dollars.
It's hard to say no to...

119
00:08:51,750 --> 00:08:53,456
No.

120
00:08:53,542 --> 00:08:54,998
If it's Edison, it works.

121
00:08:55,083 --> 00:08:57,870
If it works,
I'd strongly prefer it not kill anybody.

122
00:08:59,375 --> 00:09:00,455
Right.

123
00:09:29,375 --> 00:09:33,368
Thomas Edison has an unfavorable opinion
of college graduates seeking employment

124
00:09:33,458 --> 00:09:36,530
because they cannot answer
his examination questions.

125
00:09:37,375 --> 00:09:39,081
"Who composed ll Trovatore?"

126
00:09:39,167 --> 00:09:40,498
[MARGUERITE] Verdi.

127
00:09:40,583 --> 00:09:42,303
[WESTINGHOUSE]
"What is the speed of sound?"

128
00:09:42,333 --> 00:09:43,476
[MARGUERITE] Oh, a trick question.

129
00:09:43,500 --> 00:09:46,492
Sound travels at
a constantly diminishing rate of speed.

130
00:09:46,583 --> 00:09:52,283
But I believe the fastest rate on record
is 11,463 feet per second.

131
00:09:52,375 --> 00:09:54,036
[WESTINGHOUSE] How do you know all this?

132
00:09:54,125 --> 00:09:55,581
I read that this morning.

133
00:09:56,583 --> 00:09:57,618
[CHUCKLES]

134
00:10:00,292 --> 00:10:01,623
[MARGUERITE] This is different.

135
00:10:03,458 --> 00:10:04,948
I can feel it.

136
00:10:06,083 --> 00:10:08,495
You never requested a house guest before.

137
00:10:09,542 --> 00:10:10,622
Really?

138
00:10:12,375 --> 00:10:13,535
Hmm.

139
00:10:21,167 --> 00:10:23,954
- Eight minutes from the junction, sir.
- Hmm?

140
00:10:24,042 --> 00:10:25,782
The Westinghouse dinner.

141
00:10:25,875 --> 00:10:29,663
We're going home. They're tired.
I already shook enough hands today.

142
00:10:33,250 --> 00:10:34,990
[WESTINGHOUSE] Evening, Frank.

143
00:10:35,083 --> 00:10:36,664
George.

144
00:10:37,833 --> 00:10:38,868
Pardon?

145
00:10:39,917 --> 00:10:41,282
I'm not stopping.

146
00:10:43,292 --> 00:10:44,372
Right.

147
00:10:52,125 --> 00:10:54,116
[TRAIN ENGINE CHUGGING]

148
00:10:56,333 --> 00:10:58,324
[POPE] Maybe the brakes are busted.

149
00:11:00,250 --> 00:11:01,865
[WESTINGHOUSE] I doubt that.

150
00:11:26,792 --> 00:11:27,998
[SIGHS]

151
00:11:28,083 --> 00:11:30,039
An emergency came up in New York.

152
00:11:35,042 --> 00:11:38,284
[THUNDER RUMBLES]

153
00:11:39,500 --> 00:11:40,865
[HORSE WHINNIES]

154
00:11:44,958 --> 00:11:46,573
[PISTOL CLICKS]

155
00:11:51,708 --> 00:11:53,573
[POPE] Don't let him agitate you.

156
00:11:54,333 --> 00:11:55,823
This is how he is.

157
00:11:56,958 --> 00:11:59,791
Before he was a wizard,
I let him live in my basement.

158
00:12:00,750 --> 00:12:03,601
My wife wouldn't have him at the table
with us unless he cleaned himself.

159
00:12:03,625 --> 00:12:06,162
And boy, given the ultimatum,
the man ate alone.

160
00:12:06,250 --> 00:12:07,706
How does he work?

161
00:12:09,792 --> 00:12:13,080
You want to know his secret?
He engineers his own reality,

162
00:12:13,167 --> 00:12:15,533
and he looks for needles in haystacks.

163
00:12:16,458 --> 00:12:19,245
But how does he know
there's a needle in the hay to begin with?

164
00:12:19,333 --> 00:12:21,244
He doesn't. Neither do you.

165
00:12:21,333 --> 00:12:23,949
But he's so determined not to be
the second person to find it,

166
00:12:24,042 --> 00:12:26,624
he'll go stalk by stalk,
on a "what-do-you-know."

167
00:12:26,708 --> 00:12:29,950
I WILL SAY ONE GOOD THING ABOUT HIM:
He could be the richest man on earth,

168
00:12:30,042 --> 00:12:32,283
but he doesn't give a damn about money.

169
00:12:34,875 --> 00:12:37,116
What does he give a damn about?

170
00:12:41,208 --> 00:12:43,199
Mary? Talk.

171
00:12:43,292 --> 00:12:45,476
- I just want to test the resistance...
- Where's my barrette?

172
00:12:45,500 --> 00:12:47,411
- On top of your bureau.
- What's a bureau?

173
00:12:47,500 --> 00:12:49,286
It's what's under your barrette.

174
00:12:49,375 --> 00:12:52,412
Can I get you to promise on here
that you'll build me a fence?

175
00:12:52,500 --> 00:12:54,741
Ground's frozen. Needs to thaw.

176
00:12:57,625 --> 00:12:59,240
[DOT] Look, you're missing it!

177
00:13:00,208 --> 00:13:02,620
It's a baby! Still has her spots!

178
00:13:08,208 --> 00:13:09,823
[MARY] Tom, come see this.

179
00:13:12,958 --> 00:13:15,370
- Tom? Tom?
- [PHONE RINGS]

180
00:13:16,958 --> 00:13:20,030
You want half a million dollars,
make me something with your name on it

181
00:13:20,125 --> 00:13:22,161
that I can sell to General Sherman.

182
00:13:22,250 --> 00:13:24,582
Counteroffer.
How about I don't give you what you want,

183
00:13:24,667 --> 00:13:26,407
but you give me everything I want?

184
00:13:29,750 --> 00:13:33,493
We are gonna be big, big, big!

185
00:13:33,583 --> 00:13:36,700
- [DASH] Bigger than an elephant!
- And no one stops an elephant!

186
00:13:36,792 --> 00:13:38,532
Whoo! {giggles}

187
00:14:52,500 --> 00:14:54,456
[HORN BLARING]

188
00:15:19,750 --> 00:15:20,990
It'll work.

189
00:15:33,792 --> 00:15:36,408
Look, I've got to be honest.
This might not work.

190
00:15:36,500 --> 00:15:38,240
[CROWD CHUCKLES]

191
00:15:38,333 --> 00:15:41,951
Conventional wisdom has it, if you think
you're gonna fall flat on your face,

192
00:15:42,042 --> 00:15:43,782
better not do it in front of a crowd.

193
00:15:43,875 --> 00:15:45,206
[CROWD LAUGHS]

194
00:15:47,208 --> 00:15:49,369
Tonight, things could change.

195
00:15:50,042 --> 00:15:51,907
I hope they do.

196
00:15:52,583 --> 00:15:54,119
And if they do...

197
00:15:55,500 --> 00:15:57,456
they'll change there...

198
00:15:58,458 --> 00:15:59,914
and there.

199
00:16:01,750 --> 00:16:04,162
My boys and I caught in a jar

200
00:16:04,250 --> 00:16:07,572
what before now
has only flashed across the night sky.

201
00:16:09,333 --> 00:16:12,245
What say we unscrew the lid
and see what happens?

202
00:16:12,333 --> 00:16:15,040
- [CROWD CHEERING]
- You ready?

203
00:16:16,250 --> 00:16:19,287
- Three, two...
- [CROWD] Two, one!

204
00:16:19,375 --> 00:16:21,206
[CROWD CHEERING]

205
00:17:17,708 --> 00:17:21,656
[WESTINGHOUSE] The man has 100,000 feet
of copper for 87 customers.

206
00:17:21,750 --> 00:17:23,741
It will never be profitable.

207
00:17:24,625 --> 00:17:27,947
[POPE] It's a hobby for the rich.
Something to show off.

208
00:17:28,042 --> 00:17:29,657
It doesn't have to be.

209
00:17:32,125 --> 00:17:35,868
I'm securing patents on the Siemens dynamo
and the Gaulard-Gibbs transformer.

210
00:17:35,958 --> 00:17:38,415
Transformer?
That's more like a metal suitcase.

211
00:17:38,500 --> 00:17:40,866
How much did that cost?

212
00:17:40,958 --> 00:17:43,495
Edison, he picked the wrong horse.

213
00:17:44,500 --> 00:17:46,912
His current is like a hose
with a knot in it.

214
00:17:47,000 --> 00:17:49,036
He needs to sell one generator per mile.

215
00:17:49,125 --> 00:17:52,572
[POPE] You want to build an AC system.
That's too powerful for motors.

216
00:17:52,667 --> 00:17:55,625
Put doubt out of your mind
for one moment and tell me,

217
00:17:55,708 --> 00:17:57,994
what distance
do you estimate one could get

218
00:17:58,083 --> 00:17:59,914
with a single alternating dynamo?

219
00:18:00,000 --> 00:18:01,456
- A few thousand.
- Yards?

220
00:18:01,542 --> 00:18:02,873
- Miles.
- Mm-hmm.

221
00:18:02,958 --> 00:18:05,290
And how many houses could we reach?

222
00:18:05,375 --> 00:18:08,162
I suppose all of them.
What about the bulbs?

223
00:18:08,250 --> 00:18:10,206
Hiram's agreed to license me his.

224
00:18:10,292 --> 00:18:13,455
If you're gonna rip off Edison,
rip him off right. They glow bright gray.

225
00:18:13,542 --> 00:18:16,249
I just want to do a demonstration
for Edison.

226
00:18:16,333 --> 00:18:18,540
Somewhere small. Small town. Rural.

227
00:18:18,625 --> 00:18:22,117
And then he'll see
alternating is possible,

228
00:18:22,208 --> 00:18:24,574
and we partner... our system, his bulbs.

229
00:18:24,667 --> 00:18:28,831
In my opinion, which I will admit is based
solely on physics and reality,

230
00:18:28,917 --> 00:18:31,078
what you want to do is fun to talk about.

231
00:18:31,167 --> 00:18:33,123
I really don't think it can be done.

232
00:18:33,208 --> 00:18:35,449
- Why?
- Because he would've already done it.

233
00:18:43,792 --> 00:18:45,874
[MUTTERING]

234
00:19:05,917 --> 00:19:09,535
My Paris office seems to think you may be
the only man on Earth to rival me.

235
00:19:09,625 --> 00:19:12,822
- How would you like to work for me?
- Very much.

236
00:19:12,917 --> 00:19:16,205
I'm expanding to 12 cities,
building direct-current systems...

237
00:19:16,292 --> 00:19:17,623
Direct current?

238
00:19:19,833 --> 00:19:21,744
Alternating current is far more efficient.

239
00:19:21,833 --> 00:19:24,415
- [DOLL] Hickory, dickory dock...
- Higher voltage,

240
00:19:24,500 --> 00:19:26,220
greater distance. Less copper conductors...

241
00:19:26,292 --> 00:19:29,284
It's lethal, and it's too much power
for a motor to handle.

242
00:19:29,375 --> 00:19:31,115
I'm going to start you on $100 a month

243
00:19:31,208 --> 00:19:33,699
until you prove yourself worth
more or less.

244
00:19:33,792 --> 00:19:35,976
- A hundred dollars?
- If you can solve five things I can't,

245
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:38,537
I'll pay you $50,000,
and then I'll have to fire you.

246
00:19:39,542 --> 00:19:41,498
Mr. Tesla, welcome to Edison Electric.

247
00:19:41,583 --> 00:19:43,665
We make a minor invention every ten days

248
00:19:43,750 --> 00:19:45,911
and a major one every six months or so.

249
00:19:49,583 --> 00:19:52,103
[WOMAN] I have a suspicion
that though your husband's lab is but

250
00:19:52,167 --> 00:19:55,864
a hundred yards from your house, it must
seem sometimes like a hundred miles.

251
00:19:55,958 --> 00:19:57,448
No, a million.

252
00:19:58,333 --> 00:20:01,700
I've tried to find a way to stop
his brain, but it just runs and runs.

253
00:20:06,500 --> 00:20:10,038
I've heard Mr. Edison called
"the worst husband in America"

254
00:20:10,125 --> 00:20:13,083
on account of him sleeping in his lab
on your wedding night.

255
00:20:13,167 --> 00:20:15,078
I've heard the story myself.

256
00:20:18,917 --> 00:20:21,078
Well, on our wedding night,

257
00:20:21,167 --> 00:20:23,749
Tom and I left on the Albany, uh...

258
00:20:25,500 --> 00:20:27,036
boat.

259
00:20:27,125 --> 00:20:30,538
- We spent a week in Niagara Falls.
- [WOMAN WRITING]

260
00:20:30,625 --> 00:20:32,832
I thought that one week of happiness
would be enough

261
00:20:32,917 --> 00:20:35,784
to illuminate an entire lifetime.
[CHUCKLES]

262
00:20:35,875 --> 00:20:38,912
He was a dashing inventor,
and I worked for him.

263
00:20:39,000 --> 00:20:40,581
You know. I was a...

264
00:20:40,667 --> 00:20:42,248
[WRITING]

265
00:20:42,333 --> 00:20:43,994
H was a...

266
00:20:45,333 --> 00:20:46,368
uh...

267
00:20:48,875 --> 00:20:50,365
Uh... [CHUCKLES]

268
00:20:50,458 --> 00:20:51,618
H was a...

269
00:20:53,042 --> 00:20:54,157
[WOMAN] Yes?

270
00:20:55,542 --> 00:20:57,999
Um... [CHUCKLES]

271
00:20:59,000 --> 00:21:00,865
I'm sorry.

272
00:21:00,958 --> 00:21:02,698
L-I operated the...

273
00:21:08,083 --> 00:21:10,165
- Telegraph?
- Yes.

274
00:21:10,250 --> 00:21:12,286
Yes. Telegraph.

275
00:21:14,667 --> 00:21:16,373
Forgive me.

276
00:21:20,250 --> 00:21:22,332
Does he have any hobbies?

277
00:21:22,417 --> 00:21:24,032
[TRAIN RUMBLING]

278
00:21:33,333 --> 00:21:35,619
You promised them Coney Island.

279
00:21:35,708 --> 00:21:37,494
At the very least, a walk.

280
00:21:38,292 --> 00:21:40,578
We'll go on three walks tomorrow,
I promise.

281
00:21:43,917 --> 00:21:45,782
Here, why don't you take a picture?

282
00:22:04,667 --> 00:22:06,032
[MARY] Slow down!

283
00:22:07,042 --> 00:22:08,657
[INDISTINCT SHOUTING]

284
00:22:21,833 --> 00:22:25,155
It's neuralgia, brought on by eye strain.

285
00:22:25,250 --> 00:22:27,832
A good pair of spectacles
is all that's required.

286
00:22:27,917 --> 00:22:30,033
Oh, no. I'll look awful.

287
00:22:30,125 --> 00:22:32,867
No, no. No, you won't. That's impossible.

288
00:22:32,958 --> 00:22:36,405
Are you sure that's all?
She's been having terrible headaches.

289
00:22:36,500 --> 00:22:39,572
I'll leave her a vial of laudanum
until her eyes adjust.

290
00:22:39,667 --> 00:22:41,623
Thank you.

291
00:22:41,708 --> 00:22:43,198
Can you...

292
00:22:43,292 --> 00:22:46,204
Would you mind delaying the bill
for this visit?

293
00:22:47,125 --> 00:22:51,164
Well, my son would love an autograph.

294
00:22:54,375 --> 00:22:57,242
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWS]

295
00:23:19,542 --> 00:23:21,328
Christ, it's primitive.

296
00:23:23,417 --> 00:23:24,998
How much did this cost?

297
00:23:25,083 --> 00:23:27,324
- He won't tell me.
- What we need is here.

298
00:23:28,208 --> 00:23:31,245
[WESTINGHOUSE] Edison '3 current
can't travel more than one mile, Frank.

299
00:23:31,333 --> 00:23:34,655
It peters out.
He'll have to build so many DC motors

300
00:23:34,750 --> 00:23:37,537
and bury all his copper
just to power one town.

301
00:23:37,625 --> 00:23:40,822
This country will look like
a checkerboard of power plants.

302
00:23:40,917 --> 00:23:44,705
But with one AC dynamo,
we can step-up the voltage

303
00:23:44,792 --> 00:23:46,999
and reach as far as the eye can see.

304
00:23:47,083 --> 00:23:49,449
We string the wires overhead on poles.

305
00:23:49,542 --> 00:23:51,703
Less copper, more electricity.

306
00:23:51,792 --> 00:23:54,078
We're 75 percent cheaper.

307
00:23:54,167 --> 00:23:57,284
The only thing that matters here
is distance.

308
00:24:44,625 --> 00:24:48,163
Frank, this is as much yours
as it is mine.

309
00:24:48,250 --> 00:24:50,707
- I'd be proud if you'd flip the...
- I couldn't possibly.

310
00:24:50,792 --> 00:24:52,828
- Oh, don't be ridiculous.
- No, it belongs to you.

311
00:24:52,917 --> 00:24:54,957
- But you spent hours...
- George, it was your idea.

312
00:24:55,000 --> 00:24:56,490
You were the instigator.

313
00:24:56,583 --> 00:24:59,120
- [MACHINE WHIRS]
- Shall we go for a ride?

314
00:25:07,958 --> 00:25:11,075
[WESTINGHOUSE]
"To the Wizard of Menlo Park."

315
00:25:12,125 --> 00:25:14,867
As it seems your brakes have issues,

316
00:25:14,958 --> 00:25:18,701
I would be delighted to send my car
to deliver you

317
00:25:18,792 --> 00:25:21,750
to Great Barrington, Massachusetts...

318
00:25:22,875 --> 00:25:26,948
"where I have successfully
transmitted current one full mile."

319
00:25:30,625 --> 00:25:32,240
- No!
- [GLASS SHATTERS]

320
00:25:32,333 --> 00:25:34,198
How did he get the bulbs?

321
00:25:36,417 --> 00:25:39,375
What a roaring silence
from the brightest minds of America.

322
00:25:39,458 --> 00:25:43,997
- [MAN] He's using Hiram's design.
- Which Hiram stole from me!

323
00:25:46,292 --> 00:25:49,034
- Sue him.
- We did. The court upheld his patent.

324
00:25:49,125 --> 00:25:50,851
I'm talking about Westinghouse.
Find an angle.

325
00:25:50,875 --> 00:25:53,161
Take a trip to Barrington
and see for yourself.

326
00:25:53,250 --> 00:25:55,582
Is anyone even slightly irked
that 15 years of work

327
00:25:55,667 --> 00:25:57,498
is being filched
from right under your eyes?

328
00:25:58,208 --> 00:25:59,414
Not again!

329
00:25:59,500 --> 00:26:02,947
I built a system here,
and he goes shopping for patents

330
00:26:03,042 --> 00:26:06,079
to cobble together something
to legally steal what is mine.

331
00:26:07,167 --> 00:26:10,614
If the bulbs are a battle,
then nail him on the dynamos.

332
00:26:10,708 --> 00:26:12,039
We can't.

333
00:26:13,833 --> 00:26:15,744
He's not even using direct current, sir.

334
00:26:17,917 --> 00:26:19,703
He's using alternating?

335
00:26:22,375 --> 00:26:24,240
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATION]

336
00:26:31,583 --> 00:26:33,244
[HORSE AND BUGGY PASSES]

337
00:26:33,333 --> 00:26:34,573
[WOMAN] Mary?

338
00:26:35,167 --> 00:26:36,532
Mary?

339
00:26:36,625 --> 00:26:38,661
Yes, I think we should have some more tea.

340
00:26:38,750 --> 00:26:40,581
[CHUCKLES] Patricia?

341
00:26:40,667 --> 00:26:42,498
[MACHINES RUMBLING]

342
00:26:57,500 --> 00:26:58,990
[MAN] George Westinghouse?

343
00:26:59,875 --> 00:27:02,617
- Can we help you?
- I came from Thomas Edison.

344
00:27:03,542 --> 00:27:06,079
He wants me to buy one generator per mile.

345
00:27:09,750 --> 00:27:13,868
Your electricity would save 66 percent
on Edison's.

346
00:27:15,750 --> 00:27:17,832
Well, it's a proposed saving.

347
00:27:18,417 --> 00:27:21,989
And it's not "my electricity."
It's "electricity."

348
00:27:22,625 --> 00:27:25,162
I think it makes much more sense
for the taxpayers of Columbus

349
00:27:25,250 --> 00:27:27,286
to go with Westinghouse Electric.

350
00:27:28,708 --> 00:27:31,905
I don't want to compete.
I only intend to license my system.

351
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:34,161
- He's got the better bulbs.
- Why not compete?

352
00:27:34,250 --> 00:27:36,411
By now he knows.
Edison knows, I promise you.

353
00:27:36,500 --> 00:27:39,992
The man doesn't care about
getting it right, just about getting it.

354
00:27:40,083 --> 00:27:41,518
[WESTINGHOUSE] But he doesn't respond.

355
00:27:41,542 --> 00:27:43,999
[EDISON] Look, Westinghouse will never
have a complete system.

356
00:27:44,083 --> 00:27:46,726
- He can't even power a sewing machine.
- [TESLA] But I can solve that problem.

357
00:27:46,750 --> 00:27:49,913
Instead of again converting the currents
to work with a commutator,

358
00:27:50,000 --> 00:27:52,366
I would pass alternating current
differing in phase

359
00:27:52,458 --> 00:27:54,119
through two or more energizing circuits.

360
00:27:54,208 --> 00:27:56,995
You're supposed to be working on
commutators with DC dynamos.

361
00:27:57,083 --> 00:27:58,539
Well, I have.

362
00:27:58,625 --> 00:28:01,393
Look, I have done everything you have
asked, but you are making a mistake.

363
00:28:01,417 --> 00:28:03,874
- What?
- Direct current may be fine for cities

364
00:28:03,958 --> 00:28:07,746
when the buildings are close together,
but most of your country is empty spaces.

365
00:28:07,833 --> 00:28:10,791
Only high voltage can span the distance.
You are not thinking long-term.

366
00:28:10,875 --> 00:28:14,823
This technology is within your grasp.
I can build you an efficient motor.

367
00:28:14,917 --> 00:28:16,202
Have you tried it?

368
00:28:16,292 --> 00:28:17,407
No.

369
00:28:18,500 --> 00:28:20,707
Look, in my head, it is nearly completed.

370
00:28:20,792 --> 00:28:22,952
Men claim to have heads
full of sonnets and symphonies,

371
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:25,912
but their only problem seems to be
they can't quite write it down.

372
00:28:26,000 --> 00:28:29,663
- Let me try.
- No, because I can't start again!

373
00:28:29,750 --> 00:28:32,184
I got orders from Michigan.
I got a roomful of press waiting for me.

374
00:28:32,208 --> 00:28:33,914
Do what you were hired to do.

375
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:36,207
So, you will not honor your word
about the remuneration?

376
00:28:36,292 --> 00:28:38,453
- What are you talking about?
- Well, you said $50,000.

377
00:28:38,542 --> 00:28:41,784
- Are you unhappy with my contributions?
- I'm not paying you $50,000.

378
00:28:41,875 --> 00:28:43,285
That was a joke.

379
00:28:44,458 --> 00:28:46,699
[FOOTSTEPS RETREATING]

380
00:28:46,792 --> 00:28:48,908
Coconut fibers and horn shavings,
and fishing lines

381
00:28:49,000 --> 00:28:51,241
and cork and celluloid and flax

382
00:28:51,333 --> 00:28:53,540
and platinum, iron, nickel, copper, steel.

383
00:28:53,625 --> 00:28:55,991
We scoured the earth, years and years,

384
00:28:56,083 --> 00:28:59,120
trying thousands,
10,000 different combinations.

385
00:28:59,208 --> 00:29:03,030
Then George Westinghouse
saw howl did it and put on a pirate hat.

386
00:29:03,125 --> 00:29:05,616
- [REPORTERS LAUGH]
- You get vultures in every venture,

387
00:29:05,708 --> 00:29:07,414
but you've just got to keep them away.

388
00:29:07,500 --> 00:29:10,663
- So this is just how it works?
- Map-makers include mistakes in their work

389
00:29:10,750 --> 00:29:13,036
to see if anyone else is copying them.

390
00:29:13,125 --> 00:29:16,083
I don't have that luxury. I can't invent
streets to lead the world down.

391
00:29:16,167 --> 00:29:18,533
- OthenNise we all end up in the dark.
- [REPORTERS CHUCKLE]

392
00:29:18,625 --> 00:29:21,788
Good, and remember, write as much
as you can about how he's infringing.

393
00:29:22,542 --> 00:29:24,908
Thank you, Mr. Edison,
and thanks for this.

394
00:29:26,833 --> 00:29:28,539
[fiASHBULB POPS]

395
00:29:31,667 --> 00:29:33,828
Did I mention that his system's lethal?

396
00:29:34,542 --> 00:29:36,624
You reach out and touch

397
00:29:36,708 --> 00:29:40,075
a doorknob or a rail,
and, well, you become the circuit.

398
00:29:40,792 --> 00:29:43,124
Just to be clear on that point...

399
00:29:45,125 --> 00:29:46,535
Well, you die.

400
00:29:47,750 --> 00:29:50,241
With DC current,
you can reach out and touch anything

401
00:29:50,333 --> 00:29:52,995
at any stage of the line
with your bare hands.

402
00:29:53,083 --> 00:29:56,200
It's safe. It works. And it bears
the name of Edison, so it's pretty.

403
00:29:57,542 --> 00:30:01,364
Our government has been trying for some
time now to get me to invent a weapon,

404
00:30:01,458 --> 00:30:04,450
but I won't use this brain to invent
anything that hurts people.

405
00:30:04,542 --> 00:30:07,033
For that, you can shop in Pittsburgh.

406
00:30:07,125 --> 00:30:09,491
So you say
Westinghouse wants to hurt people?

407
00:30:09,583 --> 00:30:12,996
No. I can't say that. But you can.

408
00:30:24,750 --> 00:30:26,911
[MARGUERITE]
This is what he thinks of you.

409
00:30:28,083 --> 00:30:31,951
Issue a statement to the papers today.
Refute his charges.

410
00:30:32,042 --> 00:30:33,828
I'm not going to engage with this.

411
00:30:33,917 --> 00:30:36,659
We have the better system.
That speaks loudest.

412
00:30:42,833 --> 00:30:47,281
Westinghouse Electric Company
was founded at a quarter past 9:00.

413
00:30:48,917 --> 00:30:51,374
Hello. I'm George Westinghouse.
Do we have an appointment?

414
00:30:51,875 --> 00:30:53,206
North Dakota.

415
00:30:53,292 --> 00:30:54,577
New Orleans.

416
00:30:54,667 --> 00:30:55,952
Fort Worth.

417
00:30:56,042 --> 00:30:57,157
Sioux City.

418
00:30:57,250 --> 00:30:59,286
You want the good news or the good news?

419
00:30:59,375 --> 00:31:02,367
J' Hurrah, boys, hurrah J'

