00:31:06,458 --> 00:31:08,938
on what's in the glass bubble
when we should've been looking at

422
00:31:09,000 --> 00:31:11,241
is the clear opposite end of the bulb,
the corkscrew.

423
00:31:11,333 --> 00:31:12,994
- I own that.
- That you do.

424
00:31:14,375 --> 00:31:15,911
He's suing you.

425
00:31:16,583 --> 00:31:18,289
[MAN 2 ON PHONE]
This is a massive lawsuit.

426
00:31:18,375 --> 00:31:20,616
This is Edison and Morgan.

427
00:31:20,708 --> 00:31:23,370
MY ADVICE: Is there any way
that you can think of

428
00:31:23,458 --> 00:31:25,369
to beat gravity other than a corkscrew?

429
00:31:28,000 --> 00:31:30,742
[MAN 1] Westinghouse designed
a stopper to get around your corkscrew.

430
00:31:30,833 --> 00:31:32,913
It's only a matter of time
before they're everywhere.

431
00:31:34,375 --> 00:31:38,243
To tell you the truth, I am mostly looking
fonNard to using it at the lumber mills.

432
00:31:38,333 --> 00:31:40,745
Well, at the moment, we offer only light.

433
00:31:40,833 --> 00:31:44,451
In time, we'll move on
to motorized tools and appliances.

434
00:31:44,542 --> 00:31:47,124
When? I don't care what light costs.

435
00:31:48,083 --> 00:31:52,031
My home's on gas. I'm after productivity.
I don't understand.

436
00:31:52,125 --> 00:31:55,663
Edison said that electricity
can already be used in factories.

437
00:31:56,958 --> 00:31:58,494
Well, his can.

438
00:32:02,125 --> 00:32:04,116
I need to see this needle move.

439
00:32:04,208 --> 00:32:06,893
I can't step the voltage down
without blowing the whole thing to pieces.

440
00:32:06,917 --> 00:32:08,873
Come on. You must've made some progress.

441
00:32:08,958 --> 00:32:10,073
It's just not ready.

442
00:32:18,208 --> 00:32:20,119
[MACHINE HUMMING]

443
00:32:33,208 --> 00:32:35,119
- Kill it. Kill it!
- [ELECTRICITY CRACKLING]

444
00:32:38,708 --> 00:32:40,118
[SIGHS]

445
00:32:42,625 --> 00:32:44,665
[WESTINGHOUSE]
There has to be a solution out there.

446
00:32:49,792 --> 00:32:53,705
The Nikola Tesla Electric Light Company.
How does that sound?

447
00:32:53,792 --> 00:32:56,534
- When can you bring arcs to production?
- Arc lighting?

448
00:32:56,625 --> 00:33:00,038
I believe we agreed to compete for
incandescents, motors and distribution.

449
00:33:00,125 --> 00:33:01,615
Leave that to Edison.

450
00:33:01,708 --> 00:33:04,370
I am working on advanced methods
to surpass him.

451
00:33:04,458 --> 00:33:08,121
- To beat Edison? How soon?
- Only a few years.

452
00:33:08,208 --> 00:33:10,290
I need a lab, engineers, supplies.

453
00:33:10,375 --> 00:33:12,036
There are, of course, expenses.

454
00:33:12,125 --> 00:33:14,662
Oh, where do you get the cash
for those fancy silks?

455
00:33:14,750 --> 00:33:16,957
How I spend my income is my concern.

456
00:33:17,042 --> 00:33:21,035
Look, Mr. Tesla, if you need cash now,
you should sell us your patents.

457
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:23,786
And what would I receive?

458
00:33:23,875 --> 00:33:25,035
Stock.

459
00:33:25,125 --> 00:33:27,832
And later, if you succeed,
you can sell it for a killing.

460
00:33:27,917 --> 00:33:29,578
That means a fortune.

461
00:33:29,667 --> 00:33:33,285
- Yes, I know what an idiom is.
- We'll take on two-thirds of the risk.

462
00:33:33,375 --> 00:33:36,117
It's a good price
for the only thing you have to sell.

463
00:33:39,250 --> 00:33:42,572
[EDISON] Congestion of the brain?
What does that even mean?

464
00:33:42,667 --> 00:33:46,364
[DOCTOR] There's a... an occlusion hidden,

465
00:33:46,458 --> 00:33:48,744
and it expands.

466
00:33:48,833 --> 00:33:51,165
Her eyesight will likely go first,

467
00:33:51,250 --> 00:33:53,662
and then her vocabulary will fall away.

468
00:33:53,750 --> 00:33:55,206
I can't lose her.

469
00:33:57,917 --> 00:34:01,080
Working on a raised alphabet,
I'll make her a dictionary.

470
00:34:01,167 --> 00:34:03,954
[DOCTOR]
She'll gradually lose her mobility.

471
00:34:04,042 --> 00:34:05,703
I'll build her an elevator.

472
00:34:06,708 --> 00:34:07,743
Mr. Edison,

473
00:34:08,708 --> 00:34:10,619
what your wife needs...

474
00:34:11,708 --> 00:34:13,494
no man can build.

475
00:34:14,333 --> 00:34:16,244
What my wife needs, according to you,

476
00:34:16,958 --> 00:34:18,744
is a simple pair of spectacles.

477
00:34:20,500 --> 00:34:22,331
Nature will take its course.

478
00:34:25,583 --> 00:34:26,618
I, uh...

479
00:34:28,042 --> 00:34:30,408
I have to leave for New York tonight.

480
00:34:31,292 --> 00:34:32,998
It can't be avoided.

481
00:34:34,667 --> 00:34:37,864
I will attend to her
while you're away, but...

482
00:34:39,458 --> 00:34:40,664
dontfingen

483
00:34:51,708 --> 00:34:53,539
[TRAIN HORN BLOWS]

484
00:34:55,708 --> 00:34:57,348
[MORGAN] Ohio is going with Westinghouse.

485
00:34:57,375 --> 00:35:00,538
- Columbus. Zanesville.
- Zanesville? Give it to him.

486
00:35:00,625 --> 00:35:01,740
That isn't funny.

487
00:35:03,000 --> 00:35:05,787
We don't know something is a pattern
till it happens again,

488
00:35:05,875 --> 00:35:07,911
which I sincerely hope it does not.

489
00:35:08,000 --> 00:35:11,663
Now, you tell me, what is he doing right
that you're doing wrong?

490
00:35:11,750 --> 00:35:14,617
He is successfully selling machines
that will result

491
00:35:14,708 --> 00:35:17,165
in the accidental deaths of human beings.

492
00:35:17,250 --> 00:35:19,309
- And where are these deaths?
- Where are these deaths?

493
00:35:19,333 --> 00:35:20,448
Why don't we switch now,

494
00:35:20,542 --> 00:35:22,726
and then you get to shoulder
the inevitable suits of manslaughter.

495
00:35:22,750 --> 00:35:26,743
I think that people aren't dying because
it's not as dangerous as you wish it were.

496
00:35:28,708 --> 00:35:31,620
All right, he's beating us on costs,
but that is a temporary advantage.

497
00:35:31,708 --> 00:35:33,664
You give me enough time,
I'll make ours so cheap

498
00:35:33,750 --> 00:35:35,832
that only the rich will burn candles.

499
00:35:35,917 --> 00:35:38,750
And until then, you bleed cities
to Westinghouse. I'm not a bank.

500
00:35:38,833 --> 00:35:40,789
That is exactly what you are.

501
00:35:40,875 --> 00:35:44,493
We could've had this conversation by
telephone instead of you wasting my time.

502
00:35:44,583 --> 00:35:47,541
When I want to see someone, he comes.
Eye to eye. That's how it works.

503
00:35:47,625 --> 00:35:49,536
No. Here's how it works.

504
00:35:49,625 --> 00:35:53,538
I build miracles, and you continue to
give me as much goddamn money as I want.

505
00:35:54,292 --> 00:35:56,453
Oh, what? Did I squander another town?

506
00:35:56,542 --> 00:35:58,248
[THUNDER RUMBLES]

507
00:35:58,333 --> 00:36:00,073
All right, what did I lose?

508
00:37:52,208 --> 00:37:54,290
[MACHINERY WHIRRING]

509
00:37:57,250 --> 00:38:00,322
- [MARY SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY ON RECORDING]
- [EDISON'S VOICE] Say something.

510
00:38:00,417 --> 00:38:03,909
[MARY'S VOICE] Can [get you to promise
on here that you'll build me a fence?

511
00:38:05,292 --> 00:38:07,453
[EDISON'S VOICE]
Ground's frozen. Needs to thaw.

512
00:38:09,292 --> 00:38:10,953
[DOT'S VOICE] Look! You're missing it!

513
00:38:19,125 --> 00:38:20,456
[RECORDER CLICKS]

514
00:38:21,000 --> 00:38:23,960
- [MARY SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY ON RECORDING]
- [EDISON'S VOICE] Say something.

515
00:38:24,042 --> 00:38:27,455
[MARY'S VOICE] Can [get you to promise
on here that you'll build me a fence?

516
00:38:27,542 --> 00:38:29,783
[EDISON'S VOICE]
Ground's frozen. Needs to thaw.

517
00:38:31,292 --> 00:38:33,078
[DOT'S VOICE] Look! You're missing it!

518
00:38:35,542 --> 00:38:38,158
No. Now we move on
to my motor, as agreed...

519
00:38:38,250 --> 00:38:40,832
Look, we don't...
We don't want any of that.

520
00:38:40,917 --> 00:38:42,782
The arcs you built aren't selling anymore.

521
00:38:42,875 --> 00:38:45,116
We can't compete with Edison
and Westinghouse!

522
00:38:45,208 --> 00:38:48,200
Then I will take my patents
and wish you both a great misfortune.

523
00:38:48,292 --> 00:38:50,783
- Your patents?
- Yes. My patents.

524
00:38:51,333 --> 00:38:53,324
[BELL TOLLING]

525
00:39:00,042 --> 00:39:01,907
[SIGHS] Can I get you anything, sir?

526
00:39:03,167 --> 00:39:04,748
[EDISON] A time machine.

527
00:39:05,250 --> 00:39:08,572
Well, if! Ever find one, I'll travel
back to this moment and give it to you.

528
00:39:09,833 --> 00:39:11,414
Did you read over the proposal?

529
00:39:11,500 --> 00:39:15,163
I'm not diverting what I've got left
of my resources in lighting up a fair.

530
00:39:15,250 --> 00:39:17,866
It's much more than a fair, sir.
A third of this country

531
00:39:17,958 --> 00:39:22,281
will get on trains to Chicago
to try and see this City of Light.

532
00:39:22,792 --> 00:39:25,283
Every window, every streetlamp,
a sign that says,

533
00:39:25,375 --> 00:39:27,240
"The race is over, and we won."

534
00:39:28,000 --> 00:39:30,116
Why spend your final dollars
traveling this country

535
00:39:30,208 --> 00:39:32,790
to show everyone your electricity
when they're all

536
00:39:32,875 --> 00:39:35,366
traveling to the same place
to try to see it anyway?

537
00:39:35,458 --> 00:39:36,976
Because in a year, they'll rip it down.

538
00:39:37,000 --> 00:39:39,616
Only after 30 million people
have seen it, yes.

539
00:39:46,833 --> 00:39:48,619
Westinghouse is placing a bid.

540
00:40:03,167 --> 00:40:05,783
[EDISON] Nice hat. Looks expensive.

541
00:40:05,875 --> 00:40:08,207
I owned this before I worked for you,
Mr. Edison.

542
00:40:08,292 --> 00:40:11,614
I don't think you are working for me.
He's still using my bulbs.

543
00:40:11,708 --> 00:40:13,949
[MAN] His patents are in order.

544
00:40:14,042 --> 00:40:15,578
Do you want my advice?

545
00:40:16,042 --> 00:40:18,454
You keep saying
Westinghouse's current will kill people,

546
00:40:18,542 --> 00:40:21,739
so in lieu of evidence,
why don't you provide it?

547
00:40:31,042 --> 00:40:34,614
We're doing this because
when we have a complete system,

548
00:40:34,708 --> 00:40:37,871
it works, and it's Edison.

549
00:40:37,958 --> 00:40:39,368
Poor bastard.

550
00:40:40,333 --> 00:40:44,656
Well, he was gonna be slaughtered anyway.
He's not going to feel any pain, right?

551
00:40:44,750 --> 00:40:47,082
At 3,000 volts,
it'll be over before it begins.

552
00:40:47,167 --> 00:40:48,828
So there's nothing to worry about?

553
00:40:49,750 --> 00:40:52,537
But these are reporters, so you might
want to liven up a little bit.

554
00:40:53,500 --> 00:40:55,582
[HORSES WHINNYING]

555
00:40:57,125 --> 00:40:59,832
- [EDISON] Welcome to Menlo Park.
- [INDISTINCT CHATTER]

556
00:40:59,917 --> 00:41:02,203
Thank you for coming out
on this cold morning.

557
00:41:02,292 --> 00:41:04,908
- Good to see you again.
- Good morning.

558
00:41:05,000 --> 00:41:07,036
- I'm Southwick Brown.
- A pleasure.

559
00:41:07,125 --> 00:41:09,582
Now you, uh, you might all
want to stand back a little bit.

560
00:41:09,667 --> 00:41:11,749
Gus is being connected to the same current

561
00:41:11,833 --> 00:41:14,199
that Westinghouse uses from his generator.

562
00:41:14,292 --> 00:41:17,989
But there's no word yet coined
to define death by electricity,

563
00:41:18,083 --> 00:41:20,745
so I asked the men who write
the dictionaries, and I heard back

564
00:41:20,833 --> 00:41:24,405
"electro-dite," "electro-cremate"
and "dyna-mort."

565
00:41:24,500 --> 00:41:28,413
Butjust as Joe Guillotine
got his name on his invention,

566
00:41:29,083 --> 00:41:32,246
how could we rob the rightful inventor
of death by electricity

567
00:41:32,333 --> 00:41:34,619
of his due credit?

568
00:41:34,708 --> 00:41:38,530
I ask you to please be respectful
as we Westinghouse this horse.

569
00:42:00,125 --> 00:42:01,410
[SNORTS]

570
00:42:04,333 --> 00:42:06,164
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

571
00:42:08,458 --> 00:42:11,825
Mr. Edison, Southwick Brown,
Capital Punishment Commission.

572
00:42:11,917 --> 00:42:14,954
You've read, no doubt, of the botched
hangings throughout the Northeast.

573
00:42:15,042 --> 00:42:17,309
- The prisoners either choke to death...
- [MAN SHOUTING INDISTINCTLY]

574
00:42:17,333 --> 00:42:19,369
Or are violently decapitated.

575
00:42:19,458 --> 00:42:21,289
The spectacle is inhumane.

576
00:42:21,375 --> 00:42:25,163
But the horse... his death
was so calm, you could call it...

577
00:42:27,458 --> 00:42:28,868
poetic.

578
00:42:28,958 --> 00:42:30,914
[GRUNTING, BONES SNAP]

579
00:42:32,125 --> 00:42:35,447
The governor of New York,
upon my personal recommendation,

580
00:42:35,542 --> 00:42:37,624
would like to explore a death device

581
00:42:37,708 --> 00:42:40,199
which uses electricity on a human being.

582
00:42:40,833 --> 00:42:44,371
It would be our honor
to award you the contract.

583
00:42:45,542 --> 00:42:47,999
- If nothing else, a pleasure.
- I beg your pardon?

584
00:42:48,083 --> 00:42:52,497
To kill a human being under the guise
of justice is... is cockeyed.

585
00:42:52,583 --> 00:42:55,040
There's a big difference
between a horse and a person.

586
00:42:55,125 --> 00:42:58,242
God humanely brings us into this world.

587
00:42:58,833 --> 00:43:02,280
Why would you reject the opportunity
to be the first man

588
00:43:02,375 --> 00:43:04,787
to humanely take us out of it?

589
00:44:04,917 --> 00:44:06,373
William.

590
00:44:08,583 --> 00:44:10,244
I killed my wife.

591
00:44:17,750 --> 00:44:19,661
[DOOR CLOSES]

592
00:44:22,125 --> 00:44:24,207
[MARY'S VOICE ON RECORDER]
I'm turning the handle.

593
00:44:25,167 --> 00:44:27,078
Maybe there's more to it than that.

594
00:44:28,083 --> 00:44:30,495
If I'm doing it wrong,
you'll never know I was fooling around

595
00:44:30,583 --> 00:44:33,370
with your phonograph or gramophone,

596
00:44:33,458 --> 00:44:35,540
whatever you end up calling it.

597
00:44:35,625 --> 00:44:37,707
And what is this thing really?

598
00:44:38,500 --> 00:44:42,072
Today's Mary is speaking
to tomorrow's Thomas.

599
00:44:42,167 --> 00:44:43,498
Or from where you sit,

600
00:44:43,583 --> 00:44:46,040
today's Tom is listening
to yesterday's Mary.

601
00:44:46,125 --> 00:44:48,832
[WIND GUSTING]

602
00:44:48,917 --> 00:44:51,283
I wonder what else you can do with it.

603
00:44:59,542 --> 00:45:01,203
Mr. Tesla,

604
00:45:01,292 --> 00:45:04,268
my son and his idiot friend tell me
you don't want to make arc lights anymore.

605
00:45:04,292 --> 00:45:05,828
Is that true?

606
00:45:05,917 --> 00:45:08,329
Don't look at him, look at me.
I'm your primary shareholder.

607
00:45:08,417 --> 00:45:10,954
No. I already completed
the arc light project.

608
00:45:11,042 --> 00:45:14,785
Completed? You covered one city:
Rahway, New Jersey.

609
00:45:14,875 --> 00:45:17,708
For the love of God, think bigger.
Philadelphia.

610
00:45:17,792 --> 00:45:20,909
You design arc lights to outfit cities.
That was your only job.

611
00:45:21,000 --> 00:45:24,072
No. My AC motor. Okay? We agreed...

612
00:45:24,167 --> 00:45:26,658
- No, I never agreed to anything.
- In this office, you said...

613
00:45:26,750 --> 00:45:27,865
Uh!

614
00:45:27,958 --> 00:45:30,290
Lane, could you wait outside for a moment?

615
00:45:37,208 --> 00:45:39,699
I'm sorry. Don't you realize
you're being fired here?

616
00:45:41,833 --> 00:45:45,621
No. Please, let me work through
what I have in my head.

617
00:45:45,708 --> 00:45:48,871
I will make you the greatest provider
of electrical power in the world.

618
00:45:48,958 --> 00:45:50,744
Better than Edison.

619
00:45:50,833 --> 00:45:53,165
I'm-I'm so close. Just a few months.

620
00:45:57,875 --> 00:46:00,662
You drop in here like you're from Neptune,

621
00:46:00,750 --> 00:46:03,492
like you got a great vision of the future

622
00:46:03,583 --> 00:46:05,684
- that no one understands but you.
- No, please don't touch.

623
00:46:05,708 --> 00:46:07,744
But you're just an immigrant.

624
00:46:08,583 --> 00:46:11,541
Head full of notions,
looking for a handout. You're not Edison.

625
00:46:11,625 --> 00:46:14,742
There's only one Edison. That's why
he's in. There's millions of you.

626
00:46:14,833 --> 00:46:18,951
Big ideas, but you can't see
the real force that moves things.

627
00:46:19,042 --> 00:46:22,000
And it's not AC/DC, it's not currents.

628
00:46:22,667 --> 00:46:24,032
It's currency.

629
00:46:24,625 --> 00:46:26,707
And that's the only motor
I'm interested in.

630
00:46:29,833 --> 00:46:33,576
These patents belong to
the Tesla Electric Light Company.

631
00:46:33,667 --> 00:46:37,239
This is now the Union Electric
and Manufacturing Company,

632
00:46:37,333 --> 00:46:39,369
and I own everything in this office.

633
00:46:40,000 --> 00:46:43,322
Patents, designs, engineers, all mine.

634
00:46:44,583 --> 00:46:47,245
Never going to be anything
named Tesla ever again.

635
00:46:48,625 --> 00:46:52,823
You take your notions
and go back where you came from.

636
00:46:58,375 --> 00:46:59,740
[DOOR CLOSES]

637
00:47:05,333 --> 00:47:07,324
He's snapping up town after town.

638
00:47:08,292 --> 00:47:11,830
Cats, dogs, sheep, 11 horses...
What more do people need to see?

639
00:47:11,917 --> 00:47:14,329
The problem is, no one's actually dying
from alternating,

640
00:47:14,417 --> 00:47:17,375
apart from your cats,
dogs, sheep and 11 horses.

641
00:47:18,667 --> 00:47:21,374
- Sir, I realize I'm only your secretary...
- Just say it.

642
00:47:21,458 --> 00:47:24,325
[SIGHS] Bring the phonograph to market.
You can make your own money.

643
00:47:24,417 --> 00:47:27,124
- No, it needs too many improvements.
- Make them. Sir.

644
00:47:28,167 --> 00:47:31,159
- Bell is ripping you off.
- Graphophone? He just switched the name.

645
00:47:31,250 --> 00:47:34,226
Direct me to a store where I can buy
yours, and I won't give him the business.

646
00:47:34,250 --> 00:47:36,366
You have a real offer on the table here.

647
00:47:37,042 --> 00:47:40,330
Half a million dollars.
Sir, take the money. You need it.

648
00:47:41,458 --> 00:47:43,449
If Bell ripped you off with the telephone,

649
00:47:43,542 --> 00:47:45,533
he'll do it again with the graphophone.

650
00:47:45,625 --> 00:47:47,786
Did you just misspeak intentionally?

651
00:47:47,875 --> 00:47:49,866
Do you want Chicago?

652
00:47:54,250 --> 00:47:55,740
All right, I'm ready.

653
00:48:16,958 --> 00:48:18,323
A dollar a ball?

654
00:48:19,125 --> 00:48:20,786
So, what's your trade?

655
00:48:20,875 --> 00:48:24,197
Inventor. I fix problems for idiots.

656
00:48:25,292 --> 00:48:28,364
Imagine dictation
without the aid of a stenographer.

657
00:48:30,125 --> 00:48:32,992
Phonographic books
that will speak to blind people.

658
00:48:33,083 --> 00:48:35,665
Reproduction of music. Talking toys.

659
00:48:36,167 --> 00:48:39,000
Clocks that will announce the time.

660
00:48:39,083 --> 00:48:41,324
The preservation of dying languages.

661
00:48:41,417 --> 00:48:43,282
Teaching of elocution.

662
00:48:43,375 --> 00:48:45,912
- You hustled us.
- Yes. No.

663
00:48:46,833 --> 00:48:48,226
I didn't come all this way to lose.

664
00:48:48,250 --> 00:48:51,572
The final capturing of the dying words
of your loved ones.

665
00:48:55,500 --> 00:48:58,572
[WOMAN] Mary had a little lamb,
his fleece was white as snow,

666
00:48:58,667 --> 00:49:01,784
and everywhere that Mary went,
the lamb was sure to go.

667
00:49:07,708 --> 00:49:11,997
Well, it's either not possible,
or I'm not the engineer I thought I was.

668
00:49:14,208 --> 00:49:17,746
And he's traveling around the country,
cooking up cats.

669
00:49:17,833 --> 00:49:20,870
George, he's playing dirty. You can too.

670
00:49:20,958 --> 00:49:21,993
Mm.

671
00:49:23,625 --> 00:49:26,082
You know, when I was a boy, my father...

672
00:49:27,333 --> 00:49:29,324
tried to whip me with a branch.

673
00:49:30,375 --> 00:49:34,288
But after the first hit,
it broke into three little pieces.

674
00:49:35,917 --> 00:49:39,239
And we just stood there, looking at
this shattered stick on the ground.

675
00:49:40,875 --> 00:49:44,413
And then I noticed there was
a leather strap hanging on the wall,

676
00:49:44,500 --> 00:49:46,707
so I pointed to it and said,

677
00:49:46,792 --> 00:49:50,205
"Look. That's the better one."

678
00:49:51,417 --> 00:49:52,873
And he stopped.

679
00:49:57,375 --> 00:50:02,039
I can take a beating, but I have
no patience for shoddy craftsmanship.

680
00:50:04,667 --> 00:50:08,455
You are gonna have a working motor
sitting next to your display in Chicago,

681
00:50:08,542 --> 00:50:11,784
come hell, high water,
or the Wizard of Menlo Park.

682
00:50:18,542 --> 00:50:20,248
- Good night, Frank.
- Good night.

683
00:50:39,000 --> 00:50:41,036
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

684
00:50:51,125 --> 00:50:52,990
[HORSE WHINNIES]

685
00:50:53,833 --> 00:50:55,789
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLES]

686
00:51:16,875 --> 00:51:18,490
[CLAMORING]

687
00:51:19,375 --> 00:51:21,366
[REPORTER] So you admit Edison was right?

688
00:51:49,875 --> 00:51:52,161
We will remember Franklin Pope...

689
00:51:53,083 --> 00:51:55,870
for his fearless dedication
to moving us fonrvard.

690
00:51:56,625 --> 00:51:59,742
He tried to see
what was hiding in plain sight.

691
00:51:59,833 --> 00:52:01,664
[VOICE FADES]

692
00:52:05,500 --> 00:52:07,161
Today, I am...

693
00:52:09,000 --> 00:52:10,956
filled less with grief than anger,

694
00:52:11,042 --> 00:52:13,499
because what happened
could've been avoided.

695
00:52:15,917 --> 00:52:18,784
Hear me now
as you have never heard me before.

696
00:52:19,625 --> 00:52:21,206
As I breathe...

697
00:52:22,792 --> 00:52:24,953
as long as Westinghouse
stays in business...

698
00:52:26,375 --> 00:52:28,411
more people will die.

699
00:52:48,542 --> 00:52:50,282
My condolences.

700
00:52:52,625 --> 00:52:55,082
Sounds like he was
more than just an employee.

701
00:53:00,167 --> 00:53:02,374
What was his name? Franklin Popes?

702
00:53:03,542 --> 00:53:05,624
Pope. Just one.

703
00:53:06,875 --> 00:53:08,957
- It's a shame.
- Mm.

704
00:53:09,042 --> 00:53:10,578
But I'm here to help.

705
00:53:11,333 --> 00:53:13,198
Now, I know that you, uh,

706
00:53:13,292 --> 00:53:15,328
you wish Edison to quiet down.

707
00:53:18,083 --> 00:53:21,575
So let me combine your companies.
Let me clean up the mess.

708
00:53:25,542 --> 00:53:29,364
You really think Westinghouse Electric
is worth $5 million?

709
00:53:29,458 --> 00:53:32,746
The value of something is the highest
number someone else is willing to pay.

710
00:53:32,833 --> 00:53:36,405
But 800 men will lose their livelihoods.

711
00:53:36,500 --> 00:53:38,661
I will keep your workers.

712
00:53:38,750 --> 00:53:42,288
I will not make the same promise
for your five-day work week.

713
00:53:42,375 --> 00:53:43,410
Mm.

714
00:53:44,917 --> 00:53:46,999
Seems like you're amenable.

715
00:53:49,667 --> 00:53:50,747
Mm.

716
00:53:57,667 --> 00:53:59,623
Which current will you use?

717
00:54:01,125 --> 00:54:03,366
Whichever Edison selects, I suppose.

718
00:54:13,250 --> 00:54:14,581
[MARGUERITE] Absurdity.

719
00:54:15,208 --> 00:54:17,119
You think I'm being absurd?

720
00:54:18,292 --> 00:54:20,157
Yes, I do.

721
00:54:20,250 --> 00:54:22,457
We're overextended, Marguerite.

722
00:54:23,583 --> 00:54:25,494
There's no shame in selling.

723
00:54:29,375 --> 00:54:32,538
What I was always after
was to partner with Edison...

724
00:54:33,583 --> 00:54:35,665
and I have the chance to do that now.

725
00:54:36,875 --> 00:54:40,823
We have no motor, so we're a train into
a mountainside anyway. It's impossible.

726
00:54:40,917 --> 00:54:43,954
I thought "impossible" wasn't a word
in your vocabulary.

727
00:54:50,083 --> 00:54:52,119
I am dissolving Westinghouse Electric.

728
00:54:52,208 --> 00:54:56,406
The proceeds will go to preserve
our other failing enterprises,

729
00:54:56,500 --> 00:55:00,573
and time itself will mend
Edison's mistakes.

730
00:55:00,667 --> 00:55:04,615
You are not a captain
who changes his course with the sea.

731
00:55:04,708 --> 00:55:06,619
We are not on a course!

732
00:55:07,208 --> 00:55:09,039
We're drowning!

733
00:55:09,125 --> 00:55:12,037
This whole thing is costing us a fortune!

734
00:55:12,125 --> 00:55:14,662
- You don't care about money.
- A fortune!

735
00:55:16,000 --> 00:55:19,163
I lived in your parents' house
while you went door-to-door.

736
00:55:19,792 --> 00:55:22,864
Do you want people saying
you stand for everything you don't?

737
00:55:22,958 --> 00:55:25,040
Using your last name as a verb?

738
00:55:25,125 --> 00:55:28,413
Well, how exactly do you suggest
I correct that, dear?

739
00:55:29,875 --> 00:55:32,992
I have you, and I had Frank.

740
00:55:34,583 --> 00:55:35,663
That's it.

741
00:55:36,917 --> 00:55:38,498
I loved the man.

742
00:55:40,292 --> 00:55:44,706
This is really nothing
but a sensible business decision.

743
00:55:46,125 --> 00:55:48,161
- George...
- That's all.

744
00:55:52,750 --> 00:55:53,990
That's all.

745
00:55:56,917 --> 00:55:58,828
[FOOTSTEPS DEPART]

746
00:56:00,708 --> 00:56:03,620
Say what you will about
George Westinghouse, he sure is nice.

747
00:56:09,750 --> 00:56:11,536
[THUNDER RUMBLES]

748
00:56:22,458 --> 00:56:24,244
[HORSE WHINNIES]

749
00:56:35,208 --> 00:56:37,950
- [PISTOL CLICKS]
- [HORSE WHINNIES]

750
00:56:39,625 --> 00:56:42,867
You've crossed into territory
for the Confederacy.

751
00:56:44,875 --> 00:56:47,912
No, I, uh, I think you're mistaken.

752
00:56:48,458 --> 00:56:50,744
- According to my map here...
- [PISTOL CLICKS]

753
00:56:50,833 --> 00:56:52,824
[WHINNIES]

754
00:57:01,917 --> 00:57:06,581
Though I mourn the loss of my colleague,
misfortune does not trump progress.

755
00:57:08,792 --> 00:57:13,115
Now, it seems to me that Mr. Edison
puts his name on everything

756
00:57:13,208 --> 00:57:16,120
because he's terrified of being forgotten.

757
00:57:17,292 --> 00:57:20,284
IF YOU WANT TO BE REMEMBERED, IT'S SIMPLE:
Shoot a president.

758
00:57:21,250 --> 00:57:24,413
But if you prefer to have
what I call a legacy,

759
00:57:24,500 --> 00:57:27,367
you leave the world
a better place than you found it.

760
00:57:28,417 --> 00:57:31,739
Thomas Alva Edison is a charlatan

761
00:57:31,833 --> 00:57:35,496
who preys on the fears of the common man

762
00:57:35,583 --> 00:57:37,699
because I have the better system.

763
00:57:39,125 --> 00:57:44,199
And because I do have the better system,
Westinghouse Electric shall endure.

764
00:57:44,292 --> 00:57:45,372
Good day.

765
00:57:46,625 --> 00:57:50,072
[MORGAN] Westinghouse has taken the lead.
He's not going away.

766
00:57:50,167 --> 00:57:53,910
And while I appreciate your lights,
Mr. Edison, I'm also your customer.

767
00:57:54,500 --> 00:57:57,242
If something comes to my door
and offers me something that I need

768
00:57:57,333 --> 00:58:00,496
that is better than what I have now,
at a cheaper price,

769
00:58:00,583 --> 00:58:03,655
why, I'd be a tool
not to invite him in for tea.

770
00:58:03,750 --> 00:58:06,662
- Is this an ultimatum?
- More of a threat.

771
00:58:06,750 --> 00:58:08,786
If you maintain
that fear is the best strategy,

772
00:58:08,875 --> 00:58:10,957
then you'd better hurry up and try harder.

773
00:58:12,542 --> 00:58:13,577
Time's up.

774
00:58:17,167 --> 00:58:19,249
[MARY'S VOICE]
man who was handsome and clever

775
00:58:19,333 --> 00:58:21,824
built a box with a crank and a lever

776
00:58:21,917 --> 00:58:25,409
to store his wife's voice,
though he made a poor choice,

777
00:58:25,500 --> 00:58:29,163
because now she can tease him forever.

778
00:58:29,250 --> 00:58:31,536
[BRAKES SCREECH]

779
00:58:31,625 --> 00:58:35,038
[MAN] I couldn't stop it if I wanted to,

780
00:58:35,542 --> 00:58:37,282
which I don't,

781
00:58:37,375 --> 00:58:40,822
because I...
I think it's a remarkable gift.

782
00:58:42,292 --> 00:58:46,205
Electricity will kill that man in Buffalo.

783
00:58:46,292 --> 00:58:49,079
We don't know the voltage.

784
00:58:49,167 --> 00:58:52,864
Too much, and he ignites.
Too little, and he's still alive.

785
00:58:53,458 --> 00:58:55,824
[VOICE ECHOES] All we need is your advice.

786
00:58:55,917 --> 00:58:59,284
How much is humane?
Where to put the electrode?

787
00:58:59,375 --> 00:59:04,244
And in exchange, I will promise you
something that I know you want.

788
00:59:06,250 --> 00:59:10,573
I will put the Westinghouse name
right out front

789
00:59:10,667 --> 00:59:14,615
as the official electricity used
to kill human beings.

790
00:59:17,000 --> 00:59:20,993
I even think we can get this chair
on display at the Chicago World's Fair.

791
00:59:22,708 --> 00:59:24,369
The future.

792
00:59:32,375 --> 00:59:34,457
My name must never be
associated with this.

793
00:59:34,542 --> 00:59:37,375
I did not provide any consultation,
and you will advertise

794
00:59:37,458 --> 00:59:40,416
that Westinghouse is the best way
to take a human life.

795
00:59:41,500 --> 00:59:43,161
You guarantee your assistance?

796
00:59:45,125 --> 00:59:47,491
You ask a question, and I'll reply.

797
00:59:51,208 --> 00:59:52,789
Burn the correspondence.

798
00:59:54,250 --> 00:59:55,786
Absolutely.

799
00:59:58,958 --> 01:00:02,280
Fauteuils and blue painted bergere.

800
01:00:02,375 --> 01:00:04,707
I sold three sets of these
last week alone.

801
01:00:07,083 --> 01:00:09,870
Oh, uh, this is your classic spindle back.

802
01:00:09,958 --> 01:00:12,870
Oh, yes. And these are framed cockpen.

803
01:00:12,958 --> 01:00:14,619
Quite popular.

804
01:00:20,958 --> 01:00:23,040
Oh, deportment style.

805
01:00:25,875 --> 01:00:28,708
Would you like four, six, eight, 12?

806
01:00:28,792 --> 01:00:29,827
Just one.

807
01:00:31,583 --> 01:00:35,451
[EDISON'S VOICE] Mr. Brown, the apparatus
consists of a stationary engine,

808
01:00:35,542 --> 01:00:39,364
a Westinghouse alternating dynamo
capable of generating 3, 000 volts,

809
01:00:39,458 --> 01:00:42,871
wood chair with headrest,
binding straps and adjustable electrodes.

810
01:00:42,958 --> 01:00:45,165
Burn. TAE.

811
01:00:53,667 --> 01:00:56,158
The voltmeter, ammeter
and switchboard controlling the current

812
01:00:56,250 --> 01:00:59,242
should be located in the execution room
for monitoring.

813
01:00:59,333 --> 01:01:00,914
Burn. TAE.

814
01:01:01,000 --> 01:01:04,447
The dynamo room is communicated
by electric signals. Burn. TAE.

815
01:01:04,542 --> 01:01:07,989
The most effective machines manufactured
by Westinghouse... Burn. TAE.

816
01:01:08,083 --> 01:01:12,156
I authorize payment of $3, 600
for your efforts.

817
01:01:12,250 --> 01:01:13,865
Burn. TAE.

818
01:01:13,958 --> 01:01:17,075
The only argument which can be
urged against "Westinghousing"

819
01:01:17,167 --> 01:01:19,249
on the score of cruel punishment is that

820
01:01:19,333 --> 01:01:21,449
the flesh may burn
at the points of contact,

821
01:01:21,542 --> 01:01:24,222
and the amount of current which can be
given without such mutilation

822
01:01:24,292 --> 01:01:26,157
is not yet known.

823
01:01:26,250 --> 01:01:28,491
Burn. TAE.

824
01:01:38,708 --> 01:01:40,948
For someone who's trying to compete
for the World's Fair,

825
01:01:41,000 --> 01:01:42,706
this death-trap business
doesn't look good.

826
01:01:42,792 --> 01:01:47,035
Yeah, I know. It's just Edison
trying to smear me, as usual.

827
01:01:47,125 --> 01:01:49,036
- Can you prove it?
- No.

828
01:01:49,125 --> 01:01:51,582
But I was thinking maybe I could stop it.

829
01:01:52,375 --> 01:01:53,740
You mean me?

830
01:01:54,875 --> 01:01:57,992
You want my advice?
Don't hire me. Save your money.

831
01:01:59,000 --> 01:02:02,242
But I do know a man who could determine

832
01:02:02,333 --> 01:02:05,575
whether Edison has an exploitable
connection with the death chair.

833
01:02:05,667 --> 01:02:09,034
No, I was thinking
we could stop him via legal means.

834
01:02:10,292 --> 01:02:12,749
- You want me to put Edison on trial?
- No.

835
01:02:12,833 --> 01:02:15,165
The chair itself. The Eighth Amendment.

836
01:02:15,250 --> 01:02:17,707
So I'm to get an ax murderer

837
01:02:17,792 --> 01:02:20,329
who readily admits he slaughtered his wife

838
01:02:20,417 --> 01:02:22,248
a what... a sustainment?

839
01:02:22,333 --> 01:02:24,164
This is about showing,

840
01:02:24,250 --> 01:02:26,992
what kind of a man is Thomas Edison?

841
01:02:29,000 --> 01:02:31,116
You just keep my name out of it.

842
01:02:31,208 --> 01:02:33,415
Does your wife know
you're paying for this?

843
01:02:33,500 --> 01:02:35,331
It was her idea.

844
01:02:38,833 --> 01:02:42,246
[MAN] What precisely makes electricity
not cruel and not inhumane?

845
01:02:42,333 --> 01:02:44,369
The velocity of the current is so great

846
01:02:44,458 --> 01:02:47,495
that the brain
is instantaneously paralyzed.

847
01:02:47,583 --> 01:02:49,289
The subject is dead

848
01:02:49,375 --> 01:02:51,991
before the nerves
can communicate any shock.

849
01:02:52,083 --> 01:02:53,948
How can you know if you haven't proof?

850
01:02:54,042 --> 01:02:55,327
I tested it...

851
01:02:56,083 --> 01:02:58,290
on a gorilla from London Zoo.

852
01:02:58,375 --> 01:03:01,913
Are you connected in any way with
any of the electric lighting companies?

853
01:03:02,000 --> 01:03:03,536
No, sir.

854
01:03:03,625 --> 01:03:07,197
The State calls Thomas Alva Edison.

855
01:03:07,292 --> 01:03:09,704
Will you explain generally

856
01:03:09,792 --> 01:03:12,283
the difference between
your continuous current

857
01:03:12,375 --> 01:03:16,072
and Mr. Westinghouse's
alternating electricity?

858
01:03:16,667 --> 01:03:19,909
A continuous current flows
like water through a pipe,

859
01:03:20,000 --> 01:03:22,207
and alternating current flows
in both directions.

860
01:03:22,292 --> 01:03:24,157
Water. That doesn't sound so dangerous.

861
01:03:24,250 --> 01:03:26,115
- Not until you drown.
- [PEOPLE CHUCKLE]

862
01:03:26,208 --> 01:03:28,995
Why don't you use
Mr. Westinghouse's current?

863
01:03:29,083 --> 01:03:31,415
- I don't like it.
- You think it's dangerous.

864
01:03:31,500 --> 01:03:32,706
Yes, I do.

865
01:03:32,792 --> 01:03:35,033
Suppose you took this...

866
01:03:36,083 --> 01:03:38,495
wicked Westinghouse current...

867
01:03:38,583 --> 01:03:41,325
the one that is going to be used
on Mr. Kemmler here...

868
01:03:42,292 --> 01:03:45,455
now, suppose you kept it up
for five or six minutes.

869
01:03:46,250 --> 01:03:48,707
At 1,500 volts,

870
01:03:48,792 --> 01:03:51,283
how long would it take
before he would feel the heat?

871
01:03:51,375 --> 01:03:54,492
Well, the temperature might rise

872
01:03:54,583 --> 01:03:56,619
four or five degrees above normal

873
01:03:56,708 --> 01:03:59,415
and continue until he was mummified.

874
01:04:00,167 --> 01:04:02,533
And this wouldn't cause considerable pain?

875
01:04:02,625 --> 01:04:04,286
- It would not.
- How do you know?

876
01:04:04,375 --> 01:04:06,741
Because I personally observed
such electricity

877
01:04:06,833 --> 01:04:08,869
being used to execute
a thousand-pound horse.

878
01:04:08,958 --> 01:04:11,184
- And did the horse feel pain?
- If he did, he didn't mention it.

879
01:04:11,208 --> 01:04:13,073
[CROWD CHUCKLES]

880
01:04:14,167 --> 01:04:16,624
Now, Mr. Edison,
there is a great degree of feeling

881
01:04:16,708 --> 01:04:18,699
between you and Mr. Westinghouse.

882
01:04:18,792 --> 01:04:21,625
[EDISON]
I do not dislike Mr. Westinghouse.

883
01:04:21,708 --> 01:04:23,828
[MAN] There is a contest
between you two, isn't there?

884
01:04:23,917 --> 01:04:25,873
That is not what this is about.

885
01:04:27,083 --> 01:04:29,244
I've been asked
as a dispassionate scientist

886
01:04:29,333 --> 01:04:32,370
to advise on the simple question
of whether death by electricity

887
01:04:32,458 --> 01:04:35,245
is a violation of the Eighth Amendment
and is cruel and unusual.

888
01:04:35,333 --> 01:04:38,655
In my expert opinion,
the only humane method of execution

889
01:04:38,750 --> 01:04:40,741
is Westinghouse alternating current.

890
01:04:40,833 --> 01:04:43,184
[MAN] Your Honor, Mr. Edison knows
that any current over 30 amperes...

891
01:04:43,208 --> 01:04:46,746
Milliamperes. If you're gonna interrupt,
do so in the proper denominations.

892
01:04:49,333 --> 01:04:50,789
Oh, thank you, Your Honor.

893
01:04:50,875 --> 01:04:52,351
- [JUDGE] It's my honor.
- [GAVEL RAPS]

894
01:04:52,375 --> 01:04:54,707
[JUDGE]
All right, that's all I need to hear.

895
01:05:03,375 --> 01:05:05,616
[CLAMORING]

896
01:05:05,708 --> 01:05:07,869
[EDISON]
What do you two lowlifes want, huh?

897
01:05:07,958 --> 01:05:09,823
[WESTINGHOUSE] Mr. Edison. Mr. Edison.

898
01:05:09,917 --> 01:05:10,952
Huh?

899
01:05:14,208 --> 01:05:15,368
Now look...

900
01:05:15,458 --> 01:05:17,351
I thought you were gonna leave
before I had a chance.

901
01:05:17,375 --> 01:05:21,038
- Mr. Edison, can I get your autograph?
- Uh, yeah, sure, I...

902
01:05:21,125 --> 01:05:23,116
William, do you mind?

903
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:37,367
I should warn you, there's one thing
that always beats justice.

904
01:05:37,458 --> 01:05:38,573
Money?

905
01:05:38,667 --> 01:05:39,702
Fame.

906
01:05:54,625 --> 01:05:57,697
- [THUNDER RUMBLES]
- [HORSE WHINNIES]

907
01:06:00,833 --> 01:06:03,324
Oh, is that a New Model Army revolver?

908
01:06:04,000 --> 01:06:06,241
What a lovely machine that is.

909
01:06:07,167 --> 01:06:09,624
- Do you know how it works?
- You want me to show you?

910
01:06:09,708 --> 01:06:13,246
Oh, I didn't mean how it fires.
I simply meant how it works.

911
01:06:14,000 --> 01:06:16,457
It's quite a device.
You should have a look.

912
01:06:16,542 --> 01:06:19,784
You see, they designed the cylinder
so the hammer

913
01:06:19,875 --> 01:06:22,241
doesn't have to sit in an empty chamber.

914
01:06:22,333 --> 01:06:25,200
So I could shoot you six times
instead of five.

915
01:06:25,292 --> 01:06:28,079
- Well, I suppose.
- [HORSE WHINNIES]

916
01:06:29,542 --> 01:06:31,749
[MAN] They both lied on the stand.

917
01:06:32,667 --> 01:06:36,239
If you're gonna take your shot,
now is the last time to fire.

918
01:06:36,333 --> 01:06:39,530
Sometimes we have to work
outside of the rules to get what's right.

919
01:06:41,542 --> 01:06:43,533
It would be nice if we didn't have to.

920
01:06:45,250 --> 01:06:46,330
Wouldn't it?

921
01:06:47,583 --> 01:06:50,199
- This doesn't make you like him.
- Mm.

922
01:06:53,167 --> 01:06:54,577
So, what will it be?

923
01:07:31,542 --> 01:07:33,407
[PIANO PLAYING]

924
01:07:39,500 --> 01:07:41,832
[PLAYING HALTINGLY]

925
01:07:50,833 --> 01:07:52,664
[PHONE RINGS]

926
01:07:52,750 --> 01:07:55,241
In my bad ear, it sounded extraordinary.

927
01:07:55,333 --> 01:07:56,493
[DASH] Father...

928
01:08:00,042 --> 01:08:01,077
Hello.

929
01:08:01,167 --> 01:08:04,000
[WESTINGHOUSE] The apparatus consists
of a stationary engine,

930
01:08:04,083 --> 01:08:06,540
a Westinghouse alternating dynamo

931
01:08:06,625 --> 01:08:09,082
capable of generating 3, 000 volts.

932
01:08:09,167 --> 01:08:11,203
Wood chair with headrest,

933
01:08:11,292 --> 01:08:14,079
- [EDISON] Where did you get that?
- I'm sending them to the paper.

934
01:08:14,167 --> 01:08:17,239
Those letters are stolen.
You can't publish them.

935
01:08:17,333 --> 01:08:19,790
- Why not?
- Because they're private correspondences.

936
01:08:19,875 --> 01:08:23,663
Mr. Edison, if you say something
about me or my company again,

937
01:08:23,750 --> 01:08:25,911
I would ask that you tell the truth.

938
01:08:27,458 --> 01:08:29,790
That would be the decent thing to do.

939
01:08:31,750 --> 01:08:32,865
Wouldn't it?

940
01:08:35,250 --> 01:08:38,947
- [EDISON] Why didn't you burn the letters?
- [BROWN] They were from Thomas Edison.

941
01:08:39,042 --> 01:08:41,829
I don't think you appreciate
that this chair is something

942
01:08:41,917 --> 01:08:44,158
to be proud of and remembered for.

943
01:08:44,250 --> 01:08:46,536
I don't even know
how much electricity you need to use.

944
01:08:46,625 --> 01:08:50,243
- You said 1,500 volts.
- I said I think 1,500 volts.

945
01:08:50,333 --> 01:08:52,995
But if all the water in his body
evaporates, then he may ignite.

946
01:08:53,083 --> 01:08:55,790
- So we lower the amount.
- Then you slowly roast him to death.

947
01:08:55,875 --> 01:08:59,413
Listen. You must listen to me.
What you're going to do is wrong.

948
01:08:59,500 --> 01:09:02,287
Now you said that it's inevitable
and somebody else will do it.

949
01:09:02,375 --> 01:09:05,617
But just because somebody else is
gonna do it doesn't mean that you have to.

950
01:09:06,667 --> 01:09:10,865
The State thanks you
for your expert opinion and your help.

951
01:09:30,375 --> 01:09:31,455
What?

952
01:09:34,458 --> 01:09:36,540
- It's not my place to say.
- Say it.

953
01:09:37,292 --> 01:09:39,999
You said you'd never build
a device that would kill anyone.

954
01:09:49,292 --> 01:09:52,204
I make something impossible,
and they rip it away from me,

955
01:09:52,292 --> 01:09:54,578
so I do it again and they do it again.

956
01:09:54,667 --> 01:09:56,908
And again. And again.

957
01:09:59,333 --> 01:10:01,164
This isn't like everything else.

958
01:10:02,917 --> 01:10:04,623
This is everything else.

959
01:10:05,917 --> 01:10:09,785
Our future is not gonna be paved
with bricks but with copper.

960
01:10:11,667 --> 01:10:15,740
Automation, transportation, communication,
and the man that controls that current

961
01:10:15,833 --> 01:10:17,789
controls that future.

962
01:10:18,958 --> 01:10:20,914
But you know Westinghouse is right.

963
01:10:22,625 --> 01:10:24,616
You don't actually believe
that a few accidents

964
01:10:24,708 --> 01:10:26,619
rule out the viability of his current.

965
01:10:26,708 --> 01:10:28,851
- You just don't want to lose.
- I have merely amplified

966
01:10:28,875 --> 01:10:30,957
what no one else
was willing to take seriously.

967
01:10:31,042 --> 01:10:33,374
No, what you did was run him over
with a 12-ton train.

968
01:10:33,458 --> 01:10:35,768
Oh, well, he's the one
that's supposed to only make brakes,

969
01:10:35,792 --> 01:10:37,783
so, who's to blame here?

970
01:10:37,875 --> 01:10:39,536
[THUNDER RUMBLES]

971
01:10:40,458 --> 01:10:42,619
Switch tonight, and you win.

972
01:10:42,708 --> 01:10:44,790
His current kills people.

973
01:10:44,875 --> 01:10:46,240
Only because you said it will!

974
01:10:46,333 --> 01:10:49,120
Listen, I either stop complaining
about the scavengers in my garden

975
01:10:49,208 --> 01:10:52,746
or build a wall so damn high that people
will never even dare to scale it.

976
01:10:52,833 --> 01:10:54,664
You are the smartest man I know.

977
01:10:54,750 --> 01:10:57,992
Beyond building miracles out of thin air,

978
01:10:58,083 --> 01:11:00,495
I was most impressed by your principles.

979
01:11:02,458 --> 01:11:05,825
You didn't invent the incandescent.
People just think you did.

980
01:11:13,125 --> 01:11:17,915
Let me welcome you to the reality
of how things come into existence.

981
01:11:18,000 --> 01:11:21,037
We all contribute.
That's what invention is.

982
01:11:21,125 --> 01:11:24,913
The salt. The grain. The heat. The heart.

983
01:11:25,000 --> 01:11:28,538
But only one man makes the bread rise.

984
01:11:30,500 --> 01:11:33,037
That's the one that puts it all together

985
01:11:33,125 --> 01:11:36,037
and makes it taste so damn good
that people will go out there

986
01:11:36,125 --> 01:11:40,368
and hand over their hard-won dollars
to buy it.

987
01:11:40,458 --> 01:11:43,450
Mr. Edison, I want you to succeed. I do.

988
01:11:45,750 --> 01:11:48,742
But you have to switch tonight,
or you'll die as PT Barnum

989
01:11:48,833 --> 01:11:50,789
rather than Sir Isaac Newton.

990
01:12:15,542 --> 01:12:17,999
[UPTON]
Though he may be unfamiliar to you,

991
01:12:18,083 --> 01:12:21,871
his studies have demonstrated
an understanding of electrical matters

992
01:12:21,958 --> 01:12:25,951
unlike anyone I have ever known,
with respect to the assembled.

993
01:12:26,042 --> 01:12:29,580
Gentlemen and lady, Nikola Tesla.

994
01:12:29,667 --> 01:12:31,328
[APPLAUSE]

995
01:12:33,042 --> 01:12:35,579
[TESLA] Straight to our ultimate question,

996
01:12:36,333 --> 01:12:37,823
yes or no-...

997
01:12:38,667 --> 01:12:41,374
Can alternating currents operate a motor?

998
01:12:43,125 --> 01:12:44,365
Yes.

999
01:12:46,042 --> 01:12:48,158
Now anyone who builds
an alternating system

1000
01:12:48,250 --> 01:12:51,663
will be able to do what Edison can
for only a third of the cost.

1001
01:12:51,750 --> 01:12:53,991
In figure two of my polyphase system,
the armature coils

1002
01:12:54,083 --> 01:12:55,948
are shown in a more advanced position.

1003
01:12:56,042 --> 01:12:58,249
2-A illustrates the corresponding
magnetic condition...

1004
01:12:58,333 --> 01:13:00,268
Synchronous motor obtained
by winding a laminated ring

1005
01:13:00,292 --> 01:13:01,601
provided with pole projections...

1006
01:13:01,625 --> 01:13:03,456
The induction is of an ideal character,

1007
01:13:03,542 --> 01:13:05,908
being always maintained
at its maximum action.

1008
01:13:06,000 --> 01:13:09,492
Mr. Tesla, have you actually built
the motor to test your theories?

1009
01:13:09,583 --> 01:13:12,495
But they are not theories.
No, I have not built it.

1010
01:13:12,583 --> 01:13:14,448
But that would prove your beliefs.

1011
01:13:14,542 --> 01:13:17,375
But they are not beliefs,
and it is absolutely immaterial to me

1012
01:13:17,458 --> 01:13:19,449
whether I run the motor in my mind
or in a shop,

1013
01:13:19,542 --> 01:13:22,375
for I have built it already
in my imagination, and it is perfect.

1014
01:13:22,458 --> 01:13:24,699
- [MAN] Are you serious?
- Almost always.

1015
01:13:30,375 --> 01:13:32,661
[KNOCK AT DOOR]

1016
01:13:34,083 --> 01:13:36,574
Hello. I'm George Westinghouse.

1017
01:13:46,667 --> 01:13:48,373
- George Westinghouse?
- Mm-hmm.

1018
01:13:48,458 --> 01:13:51,165
An engine that compresses air into a tank

1019
01:13:51,250 --> 01:13:54,322
which is taken via pipe
to each brake on the train,

1020
01:13:54,417 --> 01:13:56,703
allowing them to operate simultaneously.

1021
01:14:00,375 --> 01:14:01,581
Thank you.

1022
01:14:09,958 --> 01:14:11,198
Please.

1023
01:14:26,750 --> 01:14:29,332
I think this entire room
is slanted two degrees.

1024
01:14:33,625 --> 01:14:37,573
I sincerely appreciate you
taking the time to meet with me.

1025
01:14:37,667 --> 01:14:40,033
Are-Are you going somewhere?

1026
01:14:41,917 --> 01:14:43,498
[RUMMAGING]

1027
01:14:51,667 --> 01:14:52,702
Oh.

1028
01:14:54,625 --> 01:14:56,866
- This is it?
- [TESLA] It's Niagara Falls.

1029
01:14:56,958 --> 01:14:58,118
[WESTINGHOUSE] Yeah.

1030
01:14:58,208 --> 01:15:01,200
And ever since my school days,
I have pictured in my imagination

1031
01:15:01,292 --> 01:15:03,624
a big wheel spinning out lightning.

1032
01:15:05,292 --> 01:15:08,534
Did you know that when I first came
to this country, I worked for Mr. Edison?

1033
01:15:08,625 --> 01:15:10,456
- I did not.
- Tea?

1034
01:15:10,542 --> 01:15:12,078
Sure.

1035
01:15:12,917 --> 01:15:15,829
I fixed two of his DC generators
in one night,

1036
01:15:15,917 --> 01:15:18,033
and he called me a damn good man.

1037
01:15:19,125 --> 01:15:21,241
So, why did he not treat me that way?

1038
01:15:21,333 --> 01:15:24,496
I quit.
Tried my own company and was deceived.

1039
01:15:24,583 --> 01:15:26,869
Who was I? Some immigrant.

1040
01:15:27,917 --> 01:15:30,579
SO I TOOK THE ONLYJOB I COULD fiND:
Digging a ditch.

1041
01:15:31,917 --> 01:15:35,455
The men laughed at my fine clothes,
but at the end of the day, I had $2.

1042
01:15:38,458 --> 01:15:40,870
What was the ditch to be used for?

1043
01:15:41,875 --> 01:15:43,615
Edison Electric.

1044
01:15:44,958 --> 01:15:46,823
It felt like digging my own grave.

1045
01:15:48,458 --> 01:15:52,406
If Mr. Edison succeeds, he will set us
back so far, we may never recover.

1046
01:15:52,500 --> 01:15:54,832
The Fair must be alternating.

1047
01:15:54,917 --> 01:15:56,498
It must be my motor.

1048
01:15:57,208 --> 01:15:59,950
I have watched as the world talks
of Chicago as a symbol,

1049
01:16:00,042 --> 01:16:01,407
a City of Light.

1050
01:16:02,250 --> 01:16:05,413
All cities will have light
in your lifetime,

1051
01:16:05,500 --> 01:16:10,039
but harnessing the power of Niagara,
that is to see our future.

1052
01:16:10,125 --> 01:16:13,788
The Falls? I'm here to talk about Chicago.

1053
01:16:13,875 --> 01:16:15,285
Think beyond Chicago.

1054
01:16:15,375 --> 01:16:19,072
Energy is as fundamental
as food, as water, as air.

1055
01:16:19,167 --> 01:16:22,284
You can... You cannot say
that only those with money can eat

1056
01:16:22,375 --> 01:16:24,081
or can breathe.

1057
01:16:24,167 --> 01:16:25,976
Yes, the Falls will light up
the Eastern Seaboard.

1058
01:16:26,000 --> 01:16:28,893
Yes, there is a great fortune to be made,
and I covet a very nice walking stick

1059
01:16:28,917 --> 01:16:31,249
I saw on 63rd and Madison,
but Niagara is the proof

1060
01:16:31,333 --> 01:16:33,369
that one day we may detach power
from profit.

1061
01:16:33,458 --> 01:16:35,995
- That is how you truly win.
- Mm.

1062
01:16:36,917 --> 01:16:41,081
- How do I know you will not cheat me?
- Well, you don't.

1063
01:16:43,625 --> 01:16:46,367
But the fact is, Mr. Tesla,
I need your motor.

1064
01:16:46,458 --> 01:16:49,905
I may be able to light up the Fair,
but I still can't move a machine.

1065
01:16:50,000 --> 01:16:53,413
If we cannot reach an agreement today,
my company will die

1066
01:16:53,500 --> 01:16:55,365
right here in your hotel room.

1067
01:16:57,875 --> 01:17:01,618
But if it does perish, so might your dream
of harnessing power from Niagara.

1068
01:17:06,083 --> 01:17:08,074
So, do we have a deal?

1069
01:17:09,958 --> 01:17:11,323
Five thousand.

1070
01:17:19,083 --> 01:17:20,368
One thousand.

1071
01:17:21,833 --> 01:17:23,698
[SCOFFS, LAUGHS]

1072
01:17:29,667 --> 01:17:31,328
[COUGHING]

1073
01:17:32,375 --> 01:17:33,410
Yeah.

1074
01:17:36,167 --> 01:17:38,249
I'll give you $2.50...

1075
01:17:42,708 --> 01:17:44,073
per horsepower.

1076
01:17:45,583 --> 01:17:49,405
I'm no genius myself,
but that should be millions.

1077
01:17:52,333 --> 01:17:54,699
- May I treat you to dinner at Delmonico's?
- [DOOR OPENS]

1078
01:17:56,125 --> 01:17:58,036
All right, Mr. Tesla, time to go.

1079
01:17:58,125 --> 01:18:01,445
- No, I will not leave your slanted room.
- He hasn't paid his bill in over a month.

1080
01:18:01,500 --> 01:18:04,788
Well, how much would it cost
to keep him here for the year?

1081
01:18:04,875 --> 01:18:06,706
[TRAIN ENGINE CHUGGING]

1082
01:18:09,750 --> 01:18:12,787
I need to shed 300 men
from the gas company.

1083
01:18:16,042 --> 01:18:18,124
There's no way around it.

1084
01:18:18,917 --> 01:18:21,717
[MARGUERITE] So we pay their salaries
and move them to the electricity.

1085
01:18:21,792 --> 01:18:23,783
We can't keep doing this.

1086
01:18:24,833 --> 01:18:27,040
If we win, we won't have to.

1087
01:18:29,083 --> 01:18:30,914
You have truth on your side.

1088
01:18:33,125 --> 01:18:37,243
And whatever happens, you'll know
you never did anything but play fair.

1089
01:18:49,208 --> 01:18:50,823
I stole the letters

1090
01:18:50,917 --> 01:18:53,283
linking Edison to the death chair.

1091
01:18:54,667 --> 01:18:56,999
I gave them to the papers to smudge him.

1092
01:18:59,750 --> 01:19:01,615
I know you're disappointed in me.

1093
01:19:31,958 --> 01:19:33,789
[MORGAN] What am I looking at here?

1094
01:19:33,875 --> 01:19:37,288
An 80-foot tall tower
covered with 16,000 Edison bulbs,

1095
01:19:37,375 --> 01:19:39,206
topped with an eight-foot lighthouse.

1096
01:19:39,292 --> 01:19:41,499
That signals to the world
that we are the victors.

1097
01:19:41,583 --> 01:19:43,619
Otherwise,
how will people know that we won?

1098
01:19:44,333 --> 01:19:45,664
It's an idol.

1099
01:19:46,583 --> 01:19:48,289
It's a... signature.

1100
01:19:49,708 --> 01:19:53,030
And you'll get something that no one's
ever received from Thomas Edison before.

1101
01:19:53,125 --> 01:19:55,332
- Oh, yes? What's that?
- An apology.

1102
01:19:55,417 --> 01:19:59,456
I admit that spending has been,
well, more than anticipated,

1103
01:19:59,542 --> 01:20:02,705
but now, more than ever,
it's important you must push through.

1104
01:20:02,792 --> 01:20:06,580
Whatever Westinghouse is bidding
for the Fair, we... you must bid more.

1105
01:20:06,667 --> 01:20:07,873
I must.

1106
01:20:09,333 --> 01:20:10,368
"Must."

1107
01:20:12,625 --> 01:20:14,035
Who's Nikola Tesla?

1108
01:20:17,042 --> 01:20:18,157
What about him?

1109
01:20:18,250 --> 01:20:20,662
Well, he gave a talk at Columbia.

1110
01:20:20,750 --> 01:20:24,948
Word is, the Serb is building Westinghouse
a polyphase motor.

1111
01:20:25,542 --> 01:20:29,364
Light and power.
You can do both. He now may as well.

1112
01:20:29,458 --> 01:20:32,143
Who even knows how long it'll take them
to build a functioning model...

1113
01:20:32,167 --> 01:20:35,409
As of this morning,
you have ceded, I have here,

1114
01:20:35,500 --> 01:20:37,957
nine more cities to Westinghouse.

1115
01:20:38,042 --> 01:20:40,158
So, here's what's happening.

1116
01:20:41,208 --> 01:20:45,281
I am merging Edison Electric
with some of the other ankle-biters.

1117
01:20:45,750 --> 01:20:47,741
You are out.

1118
01:20:48,667 --> 01:20:49,873
You know why.

1119
01:20:50,750 --> 01:20:54,288
And I'm happy to tell you, if you require
this moment to be even more unpleasant.

1120
01:20:54,375 --> 01:20:56,582
You will receive stock,

1121
01:20:56,667 --> 01:20:59,033
and you will retain a seat on the board.

1122
01:21:05,708 --> 01:21:07,073
Who's gonna present? You?

1123
01:21:07,167 --> 01:21:09,783
- Good God, no.
- You tell me now?

1124
01:21:09,875 --> 01:21:11,976
I was here. I thought you deserved
to hear it face-to-face.

1125
01:21:12,000 --> 01:21:15,117
No, you didn't.
You just wanted to waste my time

1126
01:21:15,208 --> 01:21:17,324
and get me to sign autographs
for children.

1127
01:21:18,458 --> 01:21:20,601
- What are you going to call it then?
- That's your concern?

1128
01:21:20,625 --> 01:21:22,286
Edison Electric. It has to be.

1129
01:21:22,375 --> 01:21:25,867
Edison and electricity are synonymous,
Morgan. The bulb...

1130
01:21:25,958 --> 01:21:28,870
I do not attach a losing name
to a fledgling enterprise.

1131
01:21:28,958 --> 01:21:31,324
Now that your letters have leaked,
you've lost credibility.

1132
01:21:31,417 --> 01:21:32,537
- So, what is it?
- The name?

1133
01:21:32,583 --> 01:21:34,198
Yes, the goddamn name!

1134
01:21:34,292 --> 01:21:37,079
The contractjust says General Electric,
but I'll think of something.

1135
01:21:37,167 --> 01:21:38,282
I can be creative too.

1136
01:21:43,958 --> 01:21:45,038
Yeah.

1137
01:21:47,875 --> 01:21:48,955
[MORGAN] Mr. lnsull.

1138
01:21:51,292 --> 01:21:52,407
A moment.

1139
01:22:26,125 --> 01:22:27,456
[KNOCK AT DOOR]

1140
01:22:27,542 --> 01:22:28,998
- [GLASS SHATTERS]
- [EDISON SHOUTS]

1141
01:22:31,708 --> 01:22:34,666
He said they'd keep your name attached
as long as you didn't pursue action

1142
01:22:34,750 --> 01:22:36,911
or speak negatively to the press
about the merger.

1143
01:22:37,000 --> 01:22:38,331
What did he offer you?

1144
01:22:39,458 --> 01:22:41,418
- Tell me.
- Vice president, but I turned it down.

1145
01:22:41,458 --> 01:22:42,618
- You should take it.
- Why?

1146
01:22:42,708 --> 01:22:44,601
Alternating current...
What's the transmission voltage?

1147
01:22:44,625 --> 01:22:45,831
230,000 volts.

1148
01:22:45,917 --> 01:22:47,657
What's the filament on a 12,000-hour lamp?

1149
01:22:47,750 --> 01:22:49,851
- Carbonized Japanese bamboo.
- What do I eat for breakfast?

1150
01:22:49,875 --> 01:22:51,101
- Pie.
- So, what's the surprise?

1151
01:22:51,125 --> 01:22:53,958
Of course he needs you.
You're me, but a human being.

1152
01:23:02,958 --> 01:23:04,619
Look around the room.

1153
01:23:04,708 --> 01:23:06,118
- Hmm?
- Who's missing?

1154
01:23:08,208 --> 01:23:11,405
- [DOOR OPENS]
- Edison General Electric Company, please.

1155
01:23:11,500 --> 01:23:13,240
General Electric?

1156
01:23:13,333 --> 01:23:15,949
- Edison General Electric Company.
- Yes.

1157
01:23:16,042 --> 01:23:17,873
- Ah!
- [MARGUERITE WHISPERS INDISTINCTLY]

1158
01:23:31,083 --> 01:23:32,323
He's 12.

1159
01:23:32,417 --> 01:23:35,955
Mr. Insull, these are
the committee members of...

1160
01:23:36,042 --> 01:23:38,579
Listen closely.
Focus on the quality of the light.

1161
01:23:38,667 --> 01:23:40,749
I don't care what the courts say.

1162
01:23:40,833 --> 01:23:42,414
Westinghouse ripped off my bulbs,

1163
01:23:42,500 --> 01:23:45,116
and the good news for you
is he did a terrible job.

1164
01:23:45,208 --> 01:23:48,405
They are outdoor bulbs,
so they have a life of about two hours.

1165
01:23:48,500 --> 01:23:50,411
So focus on the replacement time.

1166
01:23:51,500 --> 01:23:55,163
Talk about the superiority of ours,
as if there's no competition.

1167
01:23:55,750 --> 01:23:58,287
Use terms like "standard," "purest,"

1168
01:23:58,375 --> 01:24:00,366
"the most beautiful light," et cetera.

1169
01:24:00,458 --> 01:24:03,101
Find out what kind of men they are.
There are really only two types.

1170
01:24:03,125 --> 01:24:06,538
The first believe themselves to be
practical, but they're secret dreamers.

1171
01:24:06,625 --> 01:24:08,536
They're the ones who'll take the risks.

1172
01:24:08,625 --> 01:24:11,037
The second, well, they'll smile
and thank you for the show,

1173
01:24:11,125 --> 01:24:12,831
but they'll vote with their wallets.

1174
01:24:12,917 --> 01:24:16,705
Unless Westinghouse is mortgaging
everything he's worth on this bid,

1175
01:24:16,792 --> 01:24:18,748
Morgan has you in good stead
with the money men.

1176
01:24:18,833 --> 01:24:21,449
So your only real job
is to look the dreamers in the eye

1177
01:24:21,542 --> 01:24:23,248
and promise them magic.

1178
01:24:23,333 --> 01:24:26,370
Now, explain back to me everything
that you remember about a parallel

1179
01:24:26,458 --> 01:24:28,893
and series of electric circuits
using none of the words I just said.

1180
01:24:28,917 --> 01:24:30,748
[SIGHS]

1181
01:24:30,833 --> 01:24:33,495
Though I am young,
I am an expert in these matters,

1182
01:24:33,583 --> 01:24:36,575
rivaled only really by Mr. Edison himself.

1183
01:24:36,667 --> 01:24:39,374
Should you choose Westinghouse, then...

1184
01:24:39,458 --> 01:24:41,949
then yes, there is a possibility

1185
01:24:42,042 --> 01:24:45,079
you'll be putting in jeopardy
the lives of 28 million people.

1186
01:24:46,333 --> 01:24:50,246
Even if Westinghouse were to make
even the smallest of errors,

1187
01:24:50,333 --> 01:24:52,574
unintentional, of course,

1188
01:24:52,667 --> 01:24:54,658
a visiting politician, a wife,

1189
01:24:54,750 --> 01:24:56,991
even a seven-year-old girl
may lean against a lamppost

1190
01:24:57,083 --> 01:24:58,994
and be struck dead immediately.

1191
01:24:59,667 --> 01:25:00,998
There you have it.

1192
01:25:01,083 --> 01:25:04,325
Mr. Westinghouse's brand of electricity
is fatal.

1193
01:25:04,417 --> 01:25:06,829
Thank you, Mr. lnsull.

1194
01:25:06,917 --> 01:25:08,498
Just to be clear, sir,

1195
01:25:08,583 --> 01:25:11,746
any electrical current
over 200 milliamperes can be deadly.

1196
01:25:11,833 --> 01:25:13,243
Even yours?

1197
01:25:21,208 --> 01:25:23,290
Mr. Westinghouse,
these are the committee members.

1198
01:25:23,375 --> 01:25:25,115
OF GROUNDS AND BUILDINGS:

1199
01:25:25,208 --> 01:25:27,790
Charles Schwab, Craig Cannon,

1200
01:25:27,875 --> 01:25:29,991
- Mayor Cregier, of course.
- Oh, of course.

1201
01:25:30,083 --> 01:25:32,540
Victor Lawson of the Chicago Daily News,

1202
01:25:32,625 --> 01:25:34,957
and the Honorable Judge Tree.

1203
01:25:35,042 --> 01:25:36,452
I'm Daniel Burnham.

1204
01:25:36,542 --> 01:25:40,740
Respectfully, we ask that you please
keep your remarks to one hour.

1205
01:25:40,833 --> 01:25:42,494
That won't be necessary.

1206
01:25:43,208 --> 01:25:45,449
- Here you go. Sir.
- Thank you.

1207
01:25:47,042 --> 01:25:48,202
Hmm.

1208
01:25:49,042 --> 01:25:50,122
[CHUCKLES]

1209
01:25:50,833 --> 01:25:52,573
My bid.

1210
01:25:52,667 --> 01:25:54,373
These are all your figures?

1211
01:25:54,458 --> 01:25:56,699
Yes, sir. Independent estimates.

1212
01:25:56,792 --> 01:26:00,114
Before we, uh,
get into the messy business,

1213
01:26:00,208 --> 01:26:03,325
let us begin
with this most general question:

1214
01:26:03,417 --> 01:26:08,207
Why should we grant Westinghouse Electric
the contract for the World's Fair?

1215
01:26:08,292 --> 01:26:12,956
Well, I guess because
our system works significantly better,

1216
01:26:13,042 --> 01:26:14,202
and, uh...

1217
01:26:16,542 --> 01:26:19,579
because our system
is significantly cheaper.

1218
01:26:24,750 --> 01:26:27,617
Mr. Schwab, Mr. Higinbotham, Mr. Cannon,

1219
01:26:27,708 --> 01:26:30,905
Mayor Cregier, Mr. Lawson, Judge Tree,

1220
01:26:31,000 --> 01:26:32,285
and Mr. Burnham,

1221
01:26:33,042 --> 01:26:35,954
thank you very much for your time
and your consideration.

1222
01:26:49,875 --> 01:26:52,207
Financially, it's clear.
We just take the better bid.

1223
01:26:52,292 --> 01:26:55,204
- Look, Westinghouse is dangerous.
- Potentially dangerous.

1224
01:26:55,292 --> 01:26:57,283
You even printed it in your own paper.

1225
01:26:57,375 --> 01:27:00,788
Alternating will be used
to kill that man in Buffalo.

1226
01:27:13,042 --> 01:27:14,828
[MAN] They both light up lights, right?

1227
01:27:14,917 --> 01:27:17,909
Westinghouse saves us some money.
Thomas Edison sells tickets.

1228
01:27:21,375 --> 01:27:24,208
[WESTINGHOUSE]
What I wouldn't give to flip through that.

1229
01:27:24,292 --> 01:27:26,954
It's like a handbook
to the future, isn't it?

1230
01:27:30,833 --> 01:27:33,666
- We need a clear majority, gentlemen.
- Don't you have stock in GE?

1231
01:27:33,750 --> 01:27:35,115
That's irrelevant.

1232
01:27:36,667 --> 01:27:39,579
[TESLA] No one has ever done
what you have done for me.

1233
01:27:39,667 --> 01:27:43,114
The value of something
isn't what someone's willing to pay,

1234
01:27:43,208 --> 01:27:46,371
but the value of something
is what it contributes.

1235
01:27:46,458 --> 01:27:50,076
When we vote again, Burnham,
you can telephone the winner tonight.

1236
01:27:54,625 --> 01:27:57,116
Is it true you were born
during a lightning storm?

1237
01:27:58,208 --> 01:27:59,823
- It is true.
- [CHUCKLES]

1238
01:28:02,000 --> 01:28:04,412
All right. Tell me one thing in that book.

1239
01:28:06,792 --> 01:28:09,909
Look, you and Mr. Edison, you spend
all your time on either end of the system,

1240
01:28:10,000 --> 01:28:11,911
the dynamos and the lamps.

1241
01:28:12,000 --> 01:28:14,082
But what about what is in between?

1242
01:28:14,167 --> 01:28:15,577
- The wires?
- Mm.

1243
01:28:16,667 --> 01:28:19,374
- Do we need them?
- [BILLIARD BALLS CLATTER]

1244
01:28:26,375 --> 01:28:28,081
[PHONE RINGS]

1245
01:28:34,583 --> 01:28:38,576
[WESTINGHOUSE] The problem is, despite
all the advantages of the Remington...

1246
01:28:43,000 --> 01:28:46,413
it doesn't fix the fact that
you just dampened the gunpowder.

1247
01:28:47,125 --> 01:28:49,582
[GUNSHOT ECHOES]

1248
01:29:05,417 --> 01:29:07,408
[PROJECTOR WHIRRING]

1249
01:29:18,417 --> 01:29:19,953
What's this?

1250
01:29:22,833 --> 01:29:26,451
This is gonna do for the eye
what the phonograph did for the ear.

1251
01:29:32,875 --> 01:29:33,955
Dot?

1252
01:29:45,000 --> 01:29:46,706
[CLATTERING]

1253
01:29:50,542 --> 01:29:51,577
Again.

1254
01:29:54,958 --> 01:29:56,038
Again!

1255
01:30:31,958 --> 01:30:34,040
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS]

1256
01:31:07,875 --> 01:31:09,957
[APPLAUSE]

1257
01:31:28,833 --> 01:31:30,744
Do you have any final words?

1258
01:31:33,042 --> 01:31:35,408
[WILLIAM]
I believe I'm going to a better place.

1259
01:31:37,792 --> 01:31:39,202
Goodbye, William.

1260
01:31:47,750 --> 01:31:51,197
We live in a higher civilization...

1261
01:31:52,167 --> 01:31:53,623
from this day.

1262
01:32:03,500 --> 01:32:06,116
[APPLAUSE]

1263
01:32:37,708 --> 01:32:39,573
[CHEERING]

1264
01:32:53,792 --> 01:32:56,408
[ELECTRICITY CRACKLING]

1265
01:32:58,042 --> 01:33:00,078
[PEOPLE CLAMORING]

1266
01:33:12,000 --> 01:33:15,413
[LNSULL] "An awful spectacle,
far worse than hanging."

1267
01:33:15,500 --> 01:33:19,618
GEORGE WESTINGHOUSE:
'They would have done better with an ax.'

1268
01:33:19,708 --> 01:33:21,824
Sizzling sound. A billow of smoke

1269
01:33:21,917 --> 01:33:24,249
"that filled the room
with the odor of burning hair."

1270
01:33:25,750 --> 01:33:27,832
Well, at least it happened to a murderer.

1271
01:33:29,708 --> 01:33:32,324
[EDISON] At least
they'll never use it again to kill anyone.

1272
01:33:35,500 --> 01:33:36,615
[SIGHS]

1273
01:33:39,917 --> 01:33:41,908
Soon all these people
will have electric light,

1274
01:33:42,000 --> 01:33:44,286
and no one will even remember
it ever happened.

1275
01:33:45,833 --> 01:33:48,074
I have books so full of ideas

1276
01:33:48,167 --> 01:33:51,239
it would take me more than 12 lifetimes
to execute them.

1277
01:33:52,750 --> 01:33:55,116
So let the man have his fair
and waterfall.

1278
01:34:00,417 --> 01:34:02,032
Well, for what's it's worth,

1279
01:34:02,583 --> 01:34:06,121
I'd much rather have worked for you
than Westinghouse any day.

1280
01:34:06,208 --> 01:34:07,368
Why is that?

1281
01:34:08,292 --> 01:34:10,578
Well, I wouldn't have had as much fun,
would I?

1282
01:35:11,708 --> 01:35:13,824
Have you seen much of the fair?

1283
01:35:13,917 --> 01:35:17,159
- A Muybridge lecture, Little Egypt.
- Oh, the dancer.

1284
01:35:17,250 --> 01:35:18,615
- You saw her?
- No.

1285
01:35:19,500 --> 01:35:22,617
Well, she was... If you get the time.

1286
01:35:23,542 --> 01:35:24,577
Hmm.

1287
01:35:29,583 --> 01:35:32,245
Don't you think
a fence is a unique creation?

1288
01:35:34,042 --> 01:35:37,079
Your neighbor puts one up,
and suddenly one becomes two.

1289
01:35:38,000 --> 01:35:41,413
You also have a fence.
There's only one problem.

1290
01:35:41,500 --> 01:35:44,742
You see, one person
on one side of the fence designed it,

1291
01:35:44,833 --> 01:35:47,040
one person on one side built it,

1292
01:35:47,125 --> 01:35:49,286
and one person paid for it,

1293
01:35:49,375 --> 01:35:53,118
and yet the other person receives
a fine, free fence.

1294
01:35:55,833 --> 01:35:57,789
I didn't take your ideas.

1295
01:35:58,625 --> 01:35:59,865
Mr. Edison?

1296
01:36:01,125 --> 01:36:02,160
Sure.

1297
01:36:04,000 --> 01:36:05,115
Thank you.

1298
01:36:06,125 --> 01:36:09,242
- I was wondering about one thing.
- Oh, I'm sure there were many.

1299
01:36:09,333 --> 01:36:13,201
I was gonna invite you to dinner again,

1300
01:36:13,292 --> 01:36:15,704
but I suppose now
is as good a time as any.

1301
01:36:15,792 --> 01:36:17,268
You want to know
what was in the 13-hour bulb?

1302
01:36:17,292 --> 01:36:19,453
- I know how it works.
- Yeah, I know you do.

1303
01:36:19,542 --> 01:36:21,533
I only wondered what it felt like.

1304
01:36:23,583 --> 01:36:24,948
- Pardon?
- The bulb.

1305
01:36:25,958 --> 01:36:27,323
When you knew.

1306
01:36:27,875 --> 01:36:30,241
What was the feeling in that moment?

1307
01:36:38,667 --> 01:36:40,282
I can't tell you. I mean...

1308
01:36:42,125 --> 01:36:46,824
It's impossible to describe the feeling
because it was impossible.

1309
01:36:47,750 --> 01:36:50,708
Years of work.
Ten thousand different filaments.

1310
01:36:51,208 --> 01:36:53,494
When the thread went in the bulb,
as usual,

1311
01:36:53,583 --> 01:36:56,495
we placed our bets
and the generator sputtered to life

1312
01:36:56,583 --> 01:37:00,326
and the ball began to glow, we didn't
expect anything but another failure.

1313
01:37:02,458 --> 01:37:04,414
Then something started to happen.

1314
01:37:08,083 --> 01:37:10,870
See, our best filament
only lasted ten minutes,

1315
01:37:11,583 --> 01:37:14,700
and this fluke was rounding 20,

1316
01:37:14,792 --> 01:37:16,953
so people started to chatter.

1317
01:37:17,042 --> 01:37:20,830
And 30 minutes, 40 minutes,
an hour, two hours.

1318
01:37:20,917 --> 01:37:23,033
Then people started to shout.

1319
01:37:23,125 --> 01:37:25,787
And remember,
we hadn't got past ten minutes.

1320
01:37:26,583 --> 01:37:29,871
The boys were climbing up the walls,
tearing their hair out, and...

1321
01:37:31,708 --> 01:37:33,573
because it was impossible.

1322
01:37:34,625 --> 01:37:37,992
Seven hours. Eight hours. Nine.

1323
01:37:39,500 --> 01:37:41,331
We were silent when we hit ten.

1324
01:37:43,667 --> 01:37:46,033
Just sat around that glowing bubble,

1325
01:37:46,125 --> 01:37:49,197
drunk on our own magic,
staring at it like it...

1326
01:37:49,292 --> 01:37:52,329
I don't know, like it was the baby Jesus
playing Mozart.

1327
01:37:56,000 --> 01:37:59,322
After 13 and a half hours,
the glass cracked, and I knew it.

1328
01:38:01,667 --> 01:38:03,532
The world would never be the same.

1329
01:38:05,667 --> 01:38:08,739
I'm working on something now,
something so new that...

1330
01:38:10,375 --> 01:38:14,118
people will forget that my name
was ever associated with electricity.

1331
01:38:14,208 --> 01:38:16,324
I wonder if you know what it is yet.

1332
01:38:22,500 --> 01:38:24,582
You know, I think the solution is...

1333
01:38:25,250 --> 01:38:27,286
to divide the cost of the fence.

1334
01:38:29,708 --> 01:38:32,825
Or you cannot build a fence at all.

1335
01:38:35,708 --> 01:38:37,744
Your garden would be twice as big.

1336
01:38:38,500 --> 01:38:40,491
Wouldn't it, Tom?

1337
01:38:47,958 --> 01:38:49,914
If nothing else, a pleasure.

1338
01:38:52,167 --> 01:38:53,703
Enjoy the fair, George.

1339
01:39:00,333 --> 01:39:02,540
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS]

1340
01:39:11,792 --> 01:39:15,489
[TESLA] We build monuments to speak
to the future, to say, "We were here."

1341
01:39:17,208 --> 01:39:18,664
"We have lived."

1342
01:39:20,000 --> 01:39:23,743
A true legacy
isn't what we build up to the heavens

1343
01:39:23,833 --> 01:39:25,915
or carve deep into stone.

1344
01:39:27,083 --> 01:39:29,244
Rocks will crumble,

1345
01:39:29,333 --> 01:39:30,948
paper disintegrates,

1346
01:39:35,458 --> 01:39:38,416
Only that
which isn't in the physical realm

1347
01:39:38,500 --> 01:39:41,037
and reaches in both directions
can be eternal.

1348
01:39:42,875 --> 01:39:44,285
Our ideas.

1349
01:39:46,250 --> 01:39:48,241
They are what we leave behind.

1350
01:39:49,708 --> 01:39:52,120
And only they
are what can push us forward.

1351
01:40:52,583 --> 01:40:54,744
[WATER RUSHING, WIND GUSTING]

1352
01:41:20,833 --> 01:41:22,698
[PROJECTOR WHIRRING]

